{"title_page": "Allan Jones (businessman)", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Allan Jones\n| image = Photo of Allan Jones.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = December 31, 1952\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]]\n| alma mater = [[Middle Tennessee State University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Candy Robinson (1972-75)<br/>Janie Pangle (m. 1983)\n| children = 4\n| relatives = \n}}\n'''William Allan Jones Jr.''' (born December 31, 1952) is an American businessman from [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].  He is the founder, chairman, and CEO of [[Check Into Cash]], Creditcorp, Jones Management Services, and the Community Financial Services Association, as well as several other local [[loan|lending agencies]].<ref name=woop>{{cite news|last=Pendergrass|first=Toby|date=April 1, 2011|title=WOOP Investigates The Truth about Allan Jones|url=http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|work=[[WOOP-FM]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=October 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140316020911/http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|archivedate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref name=BBB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/tn/memphis/profile/consumer-finance-companies/check-into-cash-0543-33007054|title=Check Into Cash &#124; Better Business Bureau\u00ae Profile|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref><ref name=JMS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |title=Jones Management Services |access-date=June 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316051721/http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has been called the \"father of the payday loan industry\" for founding and building the first major [[payday loan]] chain.<ref name=harpers>{{cite web|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/usury-country/|title=Usury Country &#124; Harper&#039;s Magazine|publisher=harpers.org|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJones was born on December 31, 1952, in Cleveland, Tennessee to William A. (Bill) Jones (1919\u20131981) and Virginia Slaughter Jones (1925\u20132003).<ref name=gen/>\n\nJones attended [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]], where he wrestled and won various awards and served as team captain.<ref name=woop /> He graduated in 1972. Jones credited wrestling with helping build character: \"In wrestling, I didn't have anyone to rely on but me.\" He declined wrestling scholarships to pursue a business degree at [[Middle Tennessee State University]].<ref name=matt>''The Mat''. \"Allan Jones Donates $1 Million to Build Wrestling Facilities\" by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n===Early career===\nJones left college at age 20 to help his father stabilize the family's small business, the Credit Bureau of Cleveland.<ref name=timesfp>Chattanooga Times Free Press, February 24, 2008</ref> He purchased this reporting and debt collection business in 1977 and developed it to become one of the largest credit bureau databases in the state.<ref name=cash />\n\nJones sold the credit reporting side of the business to [[Equifax]] in 1988, although he retained the name and the company's collection agency division. He then built the company to be the largest in Tennessee with offices from Memphis to Atlanta. Jones sold the company in 1998.<ref name=power />\n\nJones founded Check Into Cash in 1993. The idea arose from him seeing a former credit bureau manager who was operating out of a small service station and cashing checks with the agreement that the owner would hold the checks until the next payday before submitting them to the bank. Check Into Cash eventually grew to include 1,300 stores nationwide.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Check Into Cash ===\n[[File:Check Into Cash store.jpg|thumb|Check Into Cash store.]]\nJones' research revealed the market for small, short term, fee-based loans collateralized by the customer's signature, leading him to found Check Into Cash in 1993.<ref name=cash /> The business model was made possible after Jones allegedly donated large amounts of money to multiple state legislators in order to convince them to change laws that previously prohibited charging of what some have characterized as [[predatory lending|exorbitant interest rate]]s.<ref name=latimes/> In effect, Jones' critics charged that he bought the State legislation that allows him to do business.<ref name=harpers/> {{As of|2005}} Check Into Cash was the second largest [[payday loan]] company in the US and was planning to expand on its existing 1,300 locations.<ref name=cash />\n\n=== Community Financial Services Association ===\nJones has been credited with founding the [[Community Financial Services Association of America]], or CFSA in 1999.<ref name=woop /> CFSA is the national trade association for companies that offer small-dollar, short-term loans or payday advances. Through a code of \"Best Practices,\" CFSA members pledge to abide by responsible industry practices that ensure customers understand the cost and risk of short-term payday advances to facilitate the best financial decisions. The practices also require that members hold themselves \"to the highest standard of service\".<ref name=cfsa>[http://cfsaa.com/about-cfsa.aspx \"About CFSA\"], Community Financial Services Association of America</ref>\n\nJones said he founded CFSA after breaking away from the National Check Cashers Association, due to concerns that the NCCA, now called Financial Service Centers of America, was not giving enough attention to the payday lending industry.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Hardwick Clothes ===\n[[File:Photo of C L Hardwick.jpg|thumb|150px|C.L. Hardwick, founder of Hardwick Clothes]]\n\nIn 2014, Jones purchased [[Hardwick Clothes]], a company founded in Cleveland, in 1880. Hardwick Clothes is the oldest manufacturer of tailor-made clothing in the United States.<ref name=hardwicksale>{{cite news|title=Sewing up the deal |newspaper=Cleveland Banner |date=June 20, 2014 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718181706/http://clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHardwick Clothes, which began as Cleveland Woolen Mills, was one of two companies founded by C.L. Hardwick in the 19th century. Hardwick put his son Joseph in charge of Hardwick Stove, the family's other business, while his son George ran the clothing company. Cleveland Woolen Mills soon evolved into a manufacturing plant, making suits and other items of apparel.<ref name=hardwickhistory>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Fletcher|title=A history of our supplier, Hardwick Clothes|url=http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|accessdate=July 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812153111/http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hardwick Stove was absorbed into [[Maytag]] in 1981.\n\nThe company, known for its \"Sewn in the South\" slogan and renowned during the 1960s for making the world's best blazer, was facing bankruptcy when Jones acquired it. Jones has said he was attracted to Hardwick Clothes because it was the oldest business of its kind in America, and is convinced that the American consumer pendulum is swinging back to \"made in America.\"<ref name=hardwickhistory />\n\nWithin weeks of purchasing Hardwick Clothes, Jones named Bruce Bellusci, former executive vice president at Hart Schafner & Marx, the company's new CEO/president.<ref name=brucebellusci>{{cite news|title=Bruce Bellusci Is New President Of Hardwick Clothes|newspaper=The Chattanoogan|date=July 23, 2014|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2014/7/23/280948/Bruce-Bellusci-Is-New-President-Of.aspx}}</ref> He also recruited Hart's designer, engineer, and three top salesmen to Hardwick.\n\nIn September 2017, Jones made national headlines when he announced that Hardwick Clothes, Check Into Cash and his other companies would no longer advertise during NFL games as a response to the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|national anthem protests]] by the league's players, which the businessman called \"unpatriotic behavior.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Cleveland Businessman Allan Jones Pulls NFL Ads After National Anthem Snub |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2017/9/27/355672/Cleveland-Businessman-Allan-Jones-Pulls.aspx |work=Chattanoogan |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref> Jones was featured on the [[Fox Business Network]] discussing the decision.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=September 29, 2017|title=Tennessee business owner on pulling ads from NFL|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfR3p4GHWPI|access-date=November 19, 2017|format=Video|time= |location= |publisher=Fox Business |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref=}}</ref>\n\nJones sold Hardwick in December 2019 to the company Puerto Rico Industries for the Blind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2019/dec/16/americas-oldest-suit-maker-hnew-ownerpuerrico/510722/|title=Hardwick Clothes in Cleveland acquired by Puerto Rico nonprofit, will add 100 workers|website=timesfreepress.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n===Other business ventures===\nJones is the largest property owner in [[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley County]] and has renovated many buildings, including a former shopping mall that he altered to become a site for his companies.<ref name=woop />\n\nThe Cleveland/Bradley Chamber of Commerce awarded Jones with the M.C. Headrick Free Enterprise Award, the organization's highest honor in 2003.<ref name=woop /> That same year Jones was inducted into the [[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga]]\u2019s Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=utc>[http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php \"Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame, 2003\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308065748/http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php |date=March 8, 2011 }}, October 2003.</ref>\n\nJones was included on ''BusinessTN'' magazine's \"Power 100\" list in 2005.<ref name=power>''BusinessTN'', July 2005.</ref> Jones appeared on the cover of ''BusinessTN'' Magazine and was characterized as \"The King of Cash\". The magazine ranked Jones as one of the 20 wealthiest people in Tennessee.<ref name=cash>Drew Ruble, [http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash \"The King of Cash\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825202735/http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash |date=August 25, 2011 }}, ''BusinessTN'', July 2005</ref>\n\nIn addition to Check Into Cash, Jones has founded or purchased several affiliate agencies, including U.S. Money Shops, a [[Pawnbroker|pawn agency]], LendingFrog.com, an online lending agency, Loan By Phone, and Buy Here Pay Here USA, a [[used car]] [[car loan|finance dealer]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |last=Green|first=Alex |date=February 5, 2015 |title=The Lord of Loans: How Cleveland payday-loan pioneer Allan Jones was propelled to fame and fortune |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/feb/05/lord-loans-how-clevelands-payday-loan-pioneer-allan-jones-was-propelled-fame-and-fortune/286693/|work=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== High school wrestling support ==\n[[File:Jones_Wrestling_Center.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones Wrestling Center]]\n[[File:Allan jones wrestling.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Jones, far left, inside the Jones Wrestling Center.]]\n\nJones is the largest individual supporter of high school wrestling in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} He founded the Cleveland/Bradley Wrestling Club in 1990,<ref name=autogenerated1>''The Mat'', \"Allan Jones Donates A Million Dollars\", by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001.</ref> and provided the $1.3 million funding for the Jones Wrestling Center located on the Cleveland High School campus.<ref name=\"woop\"/> The clubs have been successful, with Jones remarking that \u201cIt has very little to do with the buildings and it has everything to do with the right coaches.\u201d<ref name=\"woop\"/>\n\nIn the 2013 state championship, Cleveland beat runner-up Wilson Central 78-4, setting a TSSAA record for the most lopsided margin of victory, most pins and quickest championship. Since the 2006-07 season, the wrestling team has won state championships in 2011, 2013 and 2014, 2015, and 2018.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Wrestling center gets funding for addition |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075249/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones received national attention when he auctioned off a 2009 King Ranch [[F-150]] four-wheel drive pickup truck autographed twice by President [[George W. Bush]]. The proceeds of the auction went to benefit Cleveland's Higher Calling Youth Wrestling Club and the National Wrestling Hall of Fame Dan Gable Museum. \n<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Jones puts Bush\u2019s truck on auction block |url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/jones-puts-bushs-truck-on-auction-block,55603  }}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\n[[File:Allan Jones Aquatic Center.jpg|thumb|Allan Jones Aquatic Center]]\n\nJones has been described as \"Cleveland\u2019s most celebrated benefactor.\"<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 1990, Jones founded MainStreet Cleveland, dedicated to the revitalization and promotion of Cleveland's historic downtown area and donated the funds for the construction of the Virgil F. Carmichael addition to the Cleveland Public Library.<ref name=woop /> He also wrote and funded Cleveland's Shade Tree Ordinance that helped the city's tree board earn the designation of Tennessee Tree Board of the Year in 2010.  Many of the trees that line the city's streets were donated by his foundation. He donated $4 million to the [[University of Tennessee]] at Knoxville for construction of a new Allan Jones Aquatic Center.<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 2011, Allan Jones contributed to the non-profit organization [[tnAchieves]], enabling it to launch its scholarship and mentoring program in all three Bradley County high schools, ensuring that every graduating senior from Cleveland High School, [[Walker Valley High School]], and [[Bradley Central High School]] had the opportunity to attend [[Cleveland State Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Carroll |title=Cleveland, Bradley Students Get College Tuition Help |publisher=WRCBtv.com |date=August 4, 2011 |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/15212583/cleveland-bradley-students-get-college-tuition-help|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Jones was awarded the first-ever honorary degree from Cleveland State during its 49th Commencement Ceremony where he was the keynote speaker. A few days later, Jones received the Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Philanthropy from the Tennessee Board of Regents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland State Honors Allan Jones with Philanthropy Award|url=http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|website=www.clevelandstateecc.edu|access-date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417070827/http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|archive-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jones received the prestigious Fred Gregg Jr. award from the Greater Chattanooga Sports Hall of Fame for significant contributions to sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregg Award going to Jones|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/local/story/2012/feb/12/gregg-award-going-to-jones/70496/|website=www.timesfreepress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Jones family gave a donation to Lee University to purchase the old First Baptist Church building in downtown Cleveland and renovate it into a music performance hall. The building was named \u201cPangle Hall\u201d in honor of Jones' wife Janie Pangle Jones. Lee University President [[Paul Conn]] said Pangle Hall was only possible due to this donation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Lee to dedicate Pangle Hall with student, faculty, alumni music |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/music/story/2014/oct/23/lee-dedicate-pangle-hall-student-faculty-alumni-mu/270183/ |work=Times Free Press |location=Chattanooga, Tennessee |date=October 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones made national headlines after he donated 43,000 pairs of eclipse-viewing sunglasses to students in six Tennessee school systems. The businessman said the donation was made to ensure students who wanted to view the solar eclipse did so only with safe, NASA-approved glasses.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Protect those eyes! Businessman focused on kids\u2019 safety|url= http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/protect-those-eyes,63715|website=www.clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Tall Betsy ==\n{{main|Tall Betsy}}\n[[File:Photo_of_Tall_Betsy,_Fort_Hill_Cemetery,_1993.jpg|thumb|Photo of Tall Betsy in Fort Hill Cemetery, 1993.]]\nJones is credited with the creation of the legend of [[Tall Betsy]], a [[Halloween]] cultural icon based in Bradley County.\n\nJones based the character on stories (local folklore) that were told to his mother, Virginia Slaughter Jones, by her mother, Marie Schultz Slaughter. Virginia and other Cleveland children being raised during the 1930s were told by their parents that if they failed to come home before dark they would likely encounter Tall Betsy, sometimes called Black Betsy or simply \"The Lady in Black.\"<ref>Woop FM.com, April 1, 2011, \u201cWOOP Investigates the Legend of Tall Betsy\u201d</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Jones' home on [[Centenary Avenue Historic District|Centenary Avenue]] was the site of a Halloween world record. According to media reports, the Jones family handed out 11,201 pieces of bubblegum from 5 pm to 8 pm.<ref name=\"site3\">[http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130 Tall Betsy to Appear at Block Party], Cleveland Daily Banner, Official Site. Retrieved October 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nTall Betsy last appeared in 1998 after drawing a Halloween crowd of 25,000, although no explanation was ever given for the goblin's disappearance. Jones later told a reporter that while the goblin may have vanished, her spirit is embedded in the hearts and minds of the Cleveland residents who saw Tall Betsy during the eighteen years from 1980 to 1998.\n\nThe 2005 Block Party was dedicated in honor of Tall Betsy's 25th anniversary. The Block Party drew the largest crowd in the event's history. Jones arranged for nationally recognized celebrities such as the cast of \"Leave It To Beaver\" and Little Richard to entertain the more than 30,000 attendees. The Tennessee legislature declared Tall Betsy the official Halloween goblin of Bradley County in 1989. In 2011 the character was the subject of a documentary film.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title='Tall Betsy' returning to life in documentary |date=October 13, 2011 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127164633/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archivedate=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Jones\u2019 son, Bailey, assumed the identity of Tall Betsy and has appeared as the goblin each year at Halloween.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tall Betsy Set to Appear at Block Party|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130|website=clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n\nJones\u2019 company Check Into Cash has received criticism for its high interest rates and for harming its customers. Most believe that payday loans target those of low-income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestcompany.com/payday-loans/company/check-into-cash|title=Check Into Cash Reviews - Real Customer Reviews|work=Best Company|access-date=January 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe April 28, 2010, episode of [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', had a segment about the payday loan industry. Maddow criticized Jones for charging people high interest rates.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/rachel-maddow-show/2010-04-28|title=The Rachel Maddow Show, Transcript 04/28/10|work=MSNBC|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', when asked about the lack of diversity in his hometown of Cleveland, Jones allegedly said, \u201cWe have just enough blacks to put together a decent basketball team \u2014 but not so many the good people of Cleveland, Tennessee need to worry about crime. That\u2019s why I can leave my keys in the car with the door unlocked\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-rivlin/portrait-of-a-subprime-le_b_602182.html|title=Portrait of a Subprime Lender: Allan Jones, Payday King|last=Rivlin|first=Gary|date=June 6, 2010|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> He noted that many of his company managers and friends are African Americans. The article cited an anonymous source who claimed some company employees referred to a black man who shines shoes as the \"Little Chocolate Man\u201d although no source for the comment was ever provided.<ref name=\":1\" /> Also in that interview, a former employee of Jones' company stated that Jones\u2019 barber shop was successful because of \u201cfemale barbers with big titties.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/news/story/2010/jun/21/check-into-cash-founder-jones-denies-racial/20871/|title=Check into Cash founder Jones denies racial remarks|last=Report|first=Staff|date=June 21, 2010|website=Times Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones denied ever making the statements to numerous media outlets and claimed he was misquoted, stating \"I gave generously of my time\u2026to assist in the preparation for writing a book, purported to fairly represent the credit needs of the middle income working population and the markets that serve them. Unfortunately, (the author) has chosen to rearrange some of my remarks to draw incorrect conclusions regarding my personal views and beliefs.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===Legal issues===\nJones was indicted on federal charges of [[wiretapping]] in 1975 after he placed a recording device on his first wife's telephone in October 1974 after she had been granted a [[restraining order]] against him, allegedly to determine if she was having an extramarital affair, which she reportedly was. Jones reportedly used information from the recordings to obtain a divorce. His indictment was dismissed by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee|local district court]] before Jones could go to trial, and this dismissal was subsequently upheld by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=United States of America, Plaintiff-Appellant, v. William Allan Jones Jr., Defendant-Appellee.|vol=542|reporter=F.2d|opinion=661|pinpoint=|court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]|date=1976|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/339314/united-states-v-william-allan-jones/|accessdate=2019-03-03|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe legality of Jones' payday loan model was challenged shortly after Check into Cash was founded.<ref name=checkhistory>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=July 12, 2018|title=Jones reflects on \u2018Check\u2019 history\n|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/allan-jones-interview,83354|work=Cleveland Daily Banner|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> Initially Jones and other payday lenders claimed that the fee charged did not constitute interest, and therefore did not violate laws capping a maximum interest on loans, which runs contrary to multiple federal laws.<ref name=latimes/> In 1997 Check Into Cash was sued in a [[class-action lawsuit]] by two Cleveland attorneys, representing multiple customers, alleging violation of the [[Truth in Lending Act]] and [[Fair Debt Collection Act]], as well as other illegal practices. Check Into Cash eventually settled the case by paying $2.2 million to the class and $500,000 in attorneys' fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|title=The Growth of Legal Loan Sharking: A Report on the Payday Loan Industry|last=Fox|first=Jean Ann|date=November 1998|website=in.gov|publisher=Consumer Federation of America|access-date=2019-03-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20170410211246/https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|archivedate=2017-04-10}}</ref> Jones then began lobbying the legislatures in multiple states to change laws which place caps on interest, which led to the passage of multiple acts including the Tennessee Deferred Presentment Services Act by the [[Tennessee General Assembly]], which permits payday lending with some restrictions.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last=Hendren|first=John|date=January 24, 1999|title=Exorbitant 'Payday Loans' Tide Over the Desperate, Line Lenders' Pockets|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jan/24/local/me-1145|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|location=Los Angeles|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> This act considers the fee to borrow money from a payday lender not to be interest, stating \"the fee, when made and collected, shall not be deemed interest for any purpose of law.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advance.lexis.com/documentpage/?pdmfid=1000516&crid=fc8945e9-47fd-4e89-b00e-81af3aa1b4e5&nodeid=ABTAARAAM&nodepath=%2FROOT%2FABT%2FABTAAR%2FABTAARAAM&level=3&haschildren=&populated=false&title=45-17-112.+Retention+of+records+--+Operating+costs+--+Deferred+presentment+procedures.&config=025054JABlOTJjNmIyNi0wYjI0LTRjZGEtYWE5ZC0zNGFhOWNhMjFlNDgKAFBvZENhdGFsb2cDFQ14bX2GfyBTaI9WcPX5&pddocfullpath=%2Fshared%2Fdocument%2Fstatutes-legislation%2Furn%3AcontentItem%3A4X8K-TXK0-R03K-4155-00008-00&ecomp=h3t7kkk&prid=2b6533eb-4139-46fd-a0d1-8f877e68d82d|title=Tennessee Code Annotated|last=|first=|date=2011|website=advance.lexis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones' first marriage was to Candace Robinson on November 25, 1972. The couple had a daughter, Courtney Elaine Jones, born in 1973. The marriage ended in 1975. On May 14, 1983, Jones married Paula \"Janie\" Pangle (born 1961) in Bradley County. They have three children: Abby (born 1984), Will (born 1988) and Bailey (born 1991).<ref>{{cite web |title=Allan Jones Challenge Gift for Intercollegiate Aquatic Center Announced |publisher=University of Tennessee |url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html |date=November 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gen>{{cite web |first=Michael T. |last=Slaughter |title=Michael T. Slaughter Genealogy |url=http://mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |accessdate=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812042405/http://www.mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |archivedate=August 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all |url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140811214930/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html|archivedate=2014-08-11}}</ref>\n\nJones' residence is called Creekridge and is located on 400 acres north of Cleveland.<ref name=times/> It consists of a more than $5 million house constructed between 2003 and 2009, as well as a football field, horse stables, a greenhouse and a classic car collection.<ref name=msnbc/> It is located near the residence of fellow businessman [[Forrest Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Alex|title=How Forrest Preston built Life Care Centers into the biggest privately held company in the industry|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/apr/27/how-forrest-preston-built-life-care-centers-biggest-privately-held-company-industry/301066/|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=timesfreepress|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> Jones previously lived in the [[Centenary Avenue Historic District]] in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"site3\"/>\n\nPolitically, Jones has been an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]], and has donated to the campaigns of both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians, but his views are characterized to be [[Right-wing politics|right-leaning]] and fiscally [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]. Jones supported [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. Presidential Election]]. A few days after the [[inauguration of President Trump]], Jones stated in an interview with [[Fox & Friends]] that he was \"tired of Presidents who were politicians\" and believed that small businesses would benefit from Trump's policies.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=January 30, 2017|title=Allan Jones on Fox and Friends|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KnkntifOTGQ&t=11s|access-date= |format= |time= |location= |publisher=Fox News|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Toby McKenzie]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://wallanjones.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Allan}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name = Allan Jones\n| image = Photo of Allan Jones.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = December 31, 1952\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality =\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]]\n| alma mater = [[Middle Tennessee State University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title =\n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party =\n| boards = \n| religion =\n| spouse = Candy Robinson (1972-75)<br/>Janie Pangle (m. 1983)\n| children = 4\n| relatives = \n}}\n'''William Allan Jones Jr.''' (born December 31, 1952) is an American businessman from [[Cleveland, Tennessee]].  He is the founder, chairman, and CEO of [[Check Into Cash]], Creditcorp, Jones Management Services, and the Community Financial Services Association, as well as several other local [[loan|lending agencies]].<ref name=woop>{{cite news|last=Pendergrass|first=Toby|date=April 1, 2011|title=WOOP Investigates The Truth about Allan Jones|url=http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|work=[[WOOP-FM]]|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=October 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140316020911/http://www.woopfm.com/a_jones_Story.htm|archivedate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref name=BBB>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbb.org/us/tn/memphis/profile/consumer-finance-companies/check-into-cash-0543-33007054|title=Check Into Cash &#124; Better Business Bureau\u00ae Profile|website=www.bbb.org}}</ref><ref name=JMS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |title=Jones Management Services |access-date=June 6, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316051721/http://www.jonesmanagement.com/welcome.htm |archive-date=March 16, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has been called the \"father of the payday loan industry\" for founding and building the first major [[payday loan]] chain.<ref name=harpers>{{cite web|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/usury-country/|title=Usury Country &#124; Harper&#039;s Magazine|publisher=harpers.org|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nJones was born on December 31, 1952, in Cleveland, Tennessee to William A. (Bill) Jones (1919\u20131981) and Virginia Slaughter Jones (1925\u20132003).<ref name=gen/>\n\nJones attended [[Cleveland High School (Tennessee)|Cleveland High School]], where he wrestled and won various awards and served as team captain.<ref name=woop /> He graduated in 1972. Jones credited wrestling with helping build character: \"In wrestling, I didn't have anyone to rely on but me.\" He declined wrestling scholarships to pursue a business degree at [[Middle Tennessee State University]].<ref name=matt>''The Mat''. \"Allan Jones Donates $1 Million to Build Wrestling Facilities\" by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\n===Early career===\nJones left college at age 20 to help his father stabilize the family's small business, the Credit Bureau of Cleveland.<ref name=timesfp>Chattanooga Times Free Press, February 24, 2008</ref> He purchased this reporting and debt collection business in 1977 and developed it to become one of the largest credit bureau databases in the state.<ref name=cash />\n\nJones sold the credit reporting side of the business to [[Equifax]] in 1988, although he retained the name and the company's collection agency division. He then built the company to be the largest in Tennessee with offices from Memphis to Atlanta. Jones sold the company in 1998.<ref name=power />\n\nJones founded Check Into Cash in 1993. The idea arose from him seeing a former credit bureau manager who was operating out of a small service station and cashing checks with the agreement that the owner would hold the checks until the next payday before submitting them to the bank. Check Into Cash eventually grew to include 1,300 stores nationwide.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Check Into Cash ===\n[[File:Check Into Cash store.jpg|thumb|Check Into Cash store.]]\nJones' research revealed the market for small, short term, fee-based loans collateralized by the customer's signature, leading him to found Check Into Cash in 1993.<ref name=cash /> The business model was made possible after Jones allegedly donated large amounts of money to multiple state legislators in order to convince them to change laws that previously prohibited charging of what some have characterized as [[predatory lending|exorbitant interest rate]]s.<ref name=latimes/> In effect, Jones' critics charged that he bought the State legislation that allows him to do business.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brook|first=Daniel|title=Usury country: Welcome to the birthplace of payday lending|journal=Harper's Magazine|date=April 2009|url=http://harpers.org/archive/2009/04/0082451|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> {{As of|2005}} Check Into Cash was the second largest [[payday loan]] company in the US and was planning to expand on its existing 1,300 locations.<ref name=cash />\n\n=== Community Financial Services Association ===\nJones has been credited with founding the [[Community Financial Services Association of America]], or CFSA in 1999.<ref name=woop /> CFSA is the national trade association for companies that offer small-dollar, short-term loans or payday advances. Through a code of \"Best Practices,\" CFSA members pledge to abide by responsible industry practices that ensure customers understand the cost and risk of short-term payday advances to facilitate the best financial decisions. The practices also require that members hold themselves \"to the highest standard of service\".<ref name=cfsa>[http://cfsaa.com/about-cfsa.aspx \"About CFSA\"], Community Financial Services Association of America</ref>\n\nJones said he founded CFSA after breaking away from the National Check Cashers Association, due to concerns that the NCCA, now called Financial Service Centers of America, was not giving enough attention to the payday lending industry.<ref name=woop />\n\n=== Hardwick Clothes ===\n[[File:Photo of C L Hardwick.jpg|thumb|150px|C.L. Hardwick, founder of Hardwick Clothes]]\n\nIn 2014, Jones purchased [[Hardwick Clothes]], a company founded in Cleveland, in 1880. Hardwick Clothes is the oldest manufacturer of tailor-made clothing in the United States.<ref name=hardwicksale>{{cite news|title=Sewing up the deal |newspaper=Cleveland Banner |date=June 20, 2014 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718181706/http://clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/25322373/article-Sewing-up-the-deal |archivedate=July 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHardwick Clothes, which began as Cleveland Woolen Mills, was one of two companies founded by C.L. Hardwick in the 19th century. Hardwick put his son Joseph in charge of Hardwick Stove, the family's other business, while his son George ran the clothing company. Cleveland Woolen Mills soon evolved into a manufacturing plant, making suits and other items of apparel.<ref name=hardwickhistory>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Fletcher|title=A history of our supplier, Hardwick Clothes|url=http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|accessdate=July 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812153111/http://seersuckerandtweeds.net/2011/06/14/127/|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Hardwick Stove was absorbed into [[Maytag]] in 1981.\n\nThe company, known for its \"Sewn in the South\" slogan and renowned during the 1960s for making the world's best blazer, was facing bankruptcy when Jones acquired it. Jones has said he was attracted to Hardwick Clothes because it was the oldest business of its kind in America, and is convinced that the American consumer pendulum is swinging back to \"made in America.\"<ref name=hardwickhistory />\n\nWithin weeks of purchasing Hardwick Clothes, Jones named Bruce Bellusci, former executive vice president at Hart Schafner & Marx, the company's new CEO/president.<ref name=brucebellusci>{{cite news|title=Bruce Bellusci Is New President Of Hardwick Clothes|newspaper=The Chattanoogan|date=July 23, 2014|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2014/7/23/280948/Bruce-Bellusci-Is-New-President-Of.aspx}}</ref> He also recruited Hart's designer, engineer, and three top salesmen to Hardwick.\n\nIn September 2017, Jones made national headlines when he announced that Hardwick Clothes, Check Into Cash and his other companies would no longer advertise during NFL games as a response to the [[U.S. national anthem protests (2016\u2013present)|national anthem protests]] by the league's players, which the businessman called \"unpatriotic behavior.\"<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=September 27, 2017 |title=Cleveland Businessman Allan Jones Pulls NFL Ads After National Anthem Snub |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2017/9/27/355672/Cleveland-Businessman-Allan-Jones-Pulls.aspx |work=Chattanoogan |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref> Jones was featured on the [[Fox Business Network]] discussing the decision.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=September 29, 2017|title=Tennessee business owner on pulling ads from NFL|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfR3p4GHWPI|access-date=November 19, 2017|format=Video|time= |location= |publisher=Fox Business |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref=}}</ref>\n\nJones sold Hardwick in December 2019 to the company Puerto Rico Industries for the Blind.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2019/dec/16/americas-oldest-suit-maker-hnew-ownerpuerrico/510722/|title=Hardwick Clothes in Cleveland acquired by Puerto Rico nonprofit, will add 100 workers|website=timesfreepress.com|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\n===Other business ventures===\nJones is the largest property owner in [[Bradley County, Tennessee|Bradley County]] and has renovated many buildings, including a former shopping mall that he altered to become a site for his companies.<ref name=woop />\n\nThe Cleveland/Bradley Chamber of Commerce awarded Jones with the M.C. Headrick Free Enterprise Award, the organization's highest honor in 2003.<ref name=woop /> That same year Jones was inducted into the [[University of Tennessee at Chattanooga]]\u2019s Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame.<ref name=utc>[http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php \"Entrepreneurship Hall of Fame, 2003\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308065748/http://www.utc.edu/Academic/HarrisChair/2003.php |date=March 8, 2011 }}, October 2003.</ref>\n\nJones was included on ''BusinessTN'' magazine's \"Power 100\" list in 2005.<ref name=power>''BusinessTN'', July 2005.</ref> Jones appeared on the cover of ''BusinessTN'' Magazine and was characterized as \"The King of Cash\". The magazine ranked Jones as one of the 20 wealthiest people in Tennessee.<ref name=cash>Drew Ruble, [http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash \"The King of Cash\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825202735/http://businesstn.com/content/king-cash |date=August 25, 2011 }}, ''BusinessTN'', July 2005</ref>\n\nIn addition to Check Into Cash, Jones has founded or purchased several affiliate agencies, including U.S. Money Shops, a [[Pawnbroker|pawn agency]], LendingFrog.com, an online lending agency, Loan By Phone, and Buy Here Pay Here USA, a [[used car]] [[car loan|finance dealer]].<ref name=times>{{cite news |last=Green|first=Alex |date=February 5, 2015 |title=The Lord of Loans: How Cleveland payday-loan pioneer Allan Jones was propelled to fame and fortune |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/feb/05/lord-loans-how-clevelands-payday-loan-pioneer-allan-jones-was-propelled-fame-and-fortune/286693/|work=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |location= |access-date=November 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n== High school wrestling support ==\n[[File:Jones_Wrestling_Center.jpg|thumb|200px|Jones Wrestling Center]]\n[[File:Allan jones wrestling.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Jones, far left, inside the Jones Wrestling Center.]]\n\nJones is the largest individual supporter of high school wrestling in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}} He founded the Cleveland/Bradley Wrestling Club in 1990,<ref name=autogenerated1>''The Mat'', \"Allan Jones Donates A Million Dollars\", by Sandra Rowland, May 23, 2001.</ref> and provided the $1.3 million funding for the Jones Wrestling Center located on the Cleveland High School campus.<ref name=\"woop\"/> The clubs have been successful, with Jones remarking that \u201cIt has very little to do with the buildings and it has everything to do with the right coaches.\u201d<ref name=\"woop\"/>\n\nIn the 2013 state championship, Cleveland beat runner-up Wilson Central 78-4, setting a TSSAA record for the most lopsided margin of victory, most pins and quickest championship. Since the 2006-07 season, the wrestling team has won state championships in 2011, 2013 and 2014, 2015, and 2018.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Wrestling center gets funding for addition |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129075249/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/24750591/article-Wrestling-center-gets-funding-for-addition |archivedate=November 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones received national attention when he auctioned off a 2009 King Ranch [[F-150]] four-wheel drive pickup truck autographed twice by President [[George W. Bush]]. The proceeds of the auction went to benefit Cleveland's Higher Calling Youth Wrestling Club and the National Wrestling Hall of Fame Dan Gable Museum. \n<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title=Jones puts Bush\u2019s truck on auction block |url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/jones-puts-bushs-truck-on-auction-block,55603  }}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\n[[File:Allan Jones Aquatic Center.jpg|thumb|Allan Jones Aquatic Center]]\n\nJones has been described as \"Cleveland\u2019s most celebrated benefactor.\"<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 1990, Jones founded MainStreet Cleveland, dedicated to the revitalization and promotion of Cleveland's historic downtown area and donated the funds for the construction of the Virgil F. Carmichael addition to the Cleveland Public Library.<ref name=woop /> He also wrote and funded Cleveland's Shade Tree Ordinance that helped the city's tree board earn the designation of Tennessee Tree Board of the Year in 2010.  Many of the trees that line the city's streets were donated by his foundation. He donated $4 million to the [[University of Tennessee]] at Knoxville for construction of a new Allan Jones Aquatic Center.<ref name=cash />\n\nIn 2011, Allan Jones contributed to the non-profit organization [[tnAchieves]], enabling it to launch its scholarship and mentoring program in all three Bradley County high schools, ensuring that every graduating senior from Cleveland High School, [[Walker Valley High School]], and [[Bradley Central High School]] had the opportunity to attend [[Cleveland State Community College]].<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Carroll |title=Cleveland, Bradley Students Get College Tuition Help |publisher=WRCBtv.com |date=August 4, 2011 |url=http://www.wrcbtv.com/story/15212583/cleveland-bradley-students-get-college-tuition-help|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2015, Jones was awarded the first-ever honorary degree from Cleveland State during its 49th Commencement Ceremony where he was the keynote speaker. A few days later, Jones received the Chancellor's Award for Excellence in Philanthropy from the Tennessee Board of Regents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cleveland State Honors Allan Jones with Philanthropy Award|url=http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|website=www.clevelandstateecc.edu|access-date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417070827/http://www.clevelandstatecc.edu/news/article/cleveland-state-honors-allan-jones-with-philanthropy-award|archive-date=April 17, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Jones received the prestigious Fred Gregg Jr. award from the Greater Chattanooga Sports Hall of Fame for significant contributions to sports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gregg Award going to Jones|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/local/story/2012/feb/12/gregg-award-going-to-jones/70496/|website=www.timesfreepress.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Jones family gave a donation to Lee University to purchase the old First Baptist Church building in downtown Cleveland and renovate it into a music performance hall. The building was named \u201cPangle Hall\u201d in honor of Jones' wife Janie Pangle Jones. Lee University President [[Paul Conn]] said Pangle Hall was only possible due to this donation.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Lee to dedicate Pangle Hall with student, faculty, alumni music |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/music/story/2014/oct/23/lee-dedicate-pangle-hall-student-faculty-alumni-mu/270183/ |work=Times Free Press |location=Chattanooga, Tennessee |date=October 23, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jones made national headlines after he donated 43,000 pairs of eclipse-viewing sunglasses to students in six Tennessee school systems. The businessman said the donation was made to ensure students who wanted to view the solar eclipse did so only with safe, NASA-approved glasses.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Protect those eyes! Businessman focused on kids\u2019 safety|url= http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/protect-those-eyes,63715|website=www.clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Tall Betsy ==\n{{main|Tall Betsy}}\n[[File:Photo_of_Tall_Betsy,_Fort_Hill_Cemetery,_1993.jpg|thumb|Photo of Tall Betsy in Fort Hill Cemetery, 1993.]]\nJones is credited with the creation of the legend of [[Tall Betsy]], a [[Halloween]] cultural icon based in Bradley County.\n\nJones based the character on stories (local folklore) that were told to his mother, Virginia Slaughter Jones, by her mother, Marie Schultz Slaughter. Virginia and other Cleveland children being raised during the 1930s were told by their parents that if they failed to come home before dark they would likely encounter Tall Betsy, sometimes called Black Betsy or simply \"The Lady in Black.\"<ref>Woop FM.com, April 1, 2011, \u201cWOOP Investigates the Legend of Tall Betsy\u201d</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Jones' home on [[Centenary Avenue Historic District|Centenary Avenue]] was the site of a Halloween world record. According to media reports, the Jones family handed out 11,201 pieces of bubblegum from 5 pm to 8 pm.<ref name=\"site3\">[http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130 Tall Betsy to Appear at Block Party], Cleveland Daily Banner, Official Site. Retrieved October 30, 2015.</ref>\n\nTall Betsy last appeared in 1998 after drawing a Halloween crowd of 25,000, although no explanation was ever given for the goblin's disappearance. Jones later told a reporter that while the goblin may have vanished, her spirit is embedded in the hearts and minds of the Cleveland residents who saw Tall Betsy during the eighteen years from 1980 to 1998.\n\nThe 2005 Block Party was dedicated in honor of Tall Betsy's 25th anniversary. The Block Party drew the largest crowd in the event's history. Jones arranged for nationally recognized celebrities such as the cast of \"Leave It To Beaver\" and Little Richard to entertain the more than 30,000 attendees. The Tennessee legislature declared Tall Betsy the official Halloween goblin of Bradley County in 1989. In 2011 the character was the subject of a documentary film.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Cleveland Daily Banner |title='Tall Betsy' returning to life in documentary |date=October 13, 2011 |url=http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127164633/http://www.clevelandbanner.com/view/full_story/15846428/article-%E2%80%98Tall-Betsy%E2%80%99-returning-to-life-in-documentary |archivedate=November 27, 2012 |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Jones\u2019 son, Bailey, assumed the identity of Tall Betsy and has appeared as the goblin each year at Halloween.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tall Betsy Set to Appear at Block Party|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/tall-betsy-set-to-appearat-block-party-730-pm,21130|website=clevelandbanner.com}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism and controversy ==\n\nJones\u2019 company Check Into Cash has received criticism for its high interest rates and for harming its customers. Most believe that payday loans target those of low-income.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://bestcompany.com/payday-loans/company/check-into-cash|title=Check Into Cash Reviews - Real Customer Reviews|work=Best Company|access-date=January 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe April 28, 2010, episode of [[MSNBC]]'s ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', had a segment about the payday loan industry. Maddow criticized Jones for charging people high interest rates.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/transcripts/rachel-maddow-show/2010-04-28|title=The Rachel Maddow Show, Transcript 04/28/10|work=MSNBC|access-date=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2010 interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', when asked about the lack of diversity in his hometown of Cleveland, Jones allegedly said, \u201cWe have just enough blacks to put together a decent basketball team \u2014 but not so many the good people of Cleveland, Tennessee need to worry about crime. That\u2019s why I can leave my keys in the car with the door unlocked\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-rivlin/portrait-of-a-subprime-le_b_602182.html|title=Portrait of a Subprime Lender: Allan Jones, Payday King|last=Rivlin|first=Gary|date=June 6, 2010|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> He noted that many of his company managers and friends are African Americans. The article cited an anonymous source who claimed some company employees referred to a black man who shines shoes as the \"Little Chocolate Man\u201d although no source for the comment was ever provided.<ref name=\":1\" /> Also in that interview, a former employee of Jones' company stated that Jones\u2019 barber shop was successful because of \u201cfemale barbers with big titties.\u201d<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/news/story/2010/jun/21/check-into-cash-founder-jones-denies-racial/20871/|title=Check into Cash founder Jones denies racial remarks|last=Report|first=Staff|date=June 21, 2010|website=Times Free Press|language=en-US|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJones denied ever making the statements to numerous media outlets and claimed he was misquoted, stating \"I gave generously of my time\u2026to assist in the preparation for writing a book, purported to fairly represent the credit needs of the middle income working population and the markets that serve them. Unfortunately, (the author) has chosen to rearrange some of my remarks to draw incorrect conclusions regarding my personal views and beliefs.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n===Legal issues===\nJones was indicted on federal charges of [[wiretapping]] in 1975 after he placed a recording device on his first wife's telephone in October 1974 after she had been granted a [[restraining order]] against him, allegedly to determine if she was having an extramarital affair, which she reportedly was. Jones reportedly used information from the recordings to obtain a divorce. His indictment was dismissed by the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Tennessee|local district court]] before Jones could go to trial, and this dismissal was subsequently upheld by the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=United States of America, Plaintiff-Appellant, v. William Allan Jones Jr., Defendant-Appellee.|vol=542|reporter=F.2d|opinion=661|pinpoint=|court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]|date=1976|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/339314/united-states-v-william-allan-jones/|accessdate=2019-03-03|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe legality of Jones' payday loan model was challenged shortly after Check into Cash was founded.<ref name=checkhistory>{{cite news|last=Bowers|first=Larry C.|date=July 12, 2018|title=Jones reflects on \u2018Check\u2019 history\n|url=http://clevelandbanner.com/stories/allan-jones-interview,83354|work=Cleveland Daily Banner|location=Cleveland, Tennessee|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> Initially Jones and other payday lenders claimed that the fee charged did not constitute interest, and therefore did not violate laws capping a maximum interest on loans, which runs contrary to multiple federal laws.<ref name=latimes/> In 1997 Check Into Cash was sued in a [[class-action lawsuit]] by two Cleveland attorneys, representing multiple customers, alleging violation of the [[Truth in Lending Act]] and [[Fair Debt Collection Act]], as well as other illegal practices. Check Into Cash eventually settled the case by paying $2.2 million to the class and $500,000 in attorneys' fees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|title=The Growth of Legal Loan Sharking: A Report on the Payday Loan Industry|last=Fox|first=Jean Ann|date=November 1998|website=in.gov|publisher=Consumer Federation of America|access-date=2019-03-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20170410211246/https://www.in.gov/dfi/2366.htm|archivedate=2017-04-10}}</ref> Jones then began lobbying the legislatures in multiple states to change laws which place caps on interest, which led to the passage of multiple acts including the Tennessee Deferred Presentment Services Act by the [[Tennessee General Assembly]], which permits payday lending with some restrictions.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|last=Hendren|first=John|date=January 24, 1999|title=Exorbitant 'Payday Loans' Tide Over the Desperate, Line Lenders' Pockets|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jan/24/local/me-1145|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|location=Los Angeles|access-date=2019-03-03}}</ref> This act considers the fee to borrow money from a payday lender not to be interest, stating \"the fee, when made and collected, shall not be deemed interest for any purpose of law.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://advance.lexis.com/documentpage/?pdmfid=1000516&crid=fc8945e9-47fd-4e89-b00e-81af3aa1b4e5&nodeid=ABTAARAAM&nodepath=%2FROOT%2FABT%2FABTAAR%2FABTAARAAM&level=3&haschildren=&populated=false&title=45-17-112.+Retention+of+records+--+Operating+costs+--+Deferred+presentment+procedures.&config=025054JABlOTJjNmIyNi0wYjI0LTRjZGEtYWE5ZC0zNGFhOWNhMjFlNDgKAFBvZENhdGFsb2cDFQ14bX2GfyBTaI9WcPX5&pddocfullpath=%2Fshared%2Fdocument%2Fstatutes-legislation%2Furn%3AcontentItem%3A4X8K-TXK0-R03K-4155-00008-00&ecomp=h3t7kkk&prid=2b6533eb-4139-46fd-a0d1-8f877e68d82d|title=Tennessee Code Annotated|last=|first=|date=2011|website=advance.lexis.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJones' first marriage was to Candace Robinson on November 25, 1972. The couple had a daughter, Courtney Elaine Jones, born in 1973. The marriage ended in 1975. On May 14, 1983, Jones married Paula \"Janie\" Pangle (born 1961) in Bradley County. They have three children: Abby (born 1984), Will (born 1988) and Bailey (born 1991).<ref>{{cite web |title=Allan Jones Challenge Gift for Intercollegiate Aquatic Center Announced |publisher=University of Tennessee |url=http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html |date=November 9, 2002 |accessdate=August 5, 2014}}</ref><ref name=gen>{{cite web |first=Michael T. |last=Slaughter |title=Michael T. Slaughter Genealogy |url=http://mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |accessdate=August 5, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812042405/http://www.mtsfamily.com/GEDGEN/grpf4074.html |archivedate=August 12, 2014 |df=mdy-all |url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140811214930/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-swim/spec-rel/110902aaa.html|archivedate=2014-08-11}}</ref>\n\nJones' residence is called Creekridge and is located on 400 acres north of Cleveland.<ref name=times/> It consists of a more than $5 million house constructed between 2003 and 2009, as well as a football field, horse stables, a greenhouse and a classic car collection.<ref name=msnbc/> It is located near the residence of fellow businessman [[Forrest Preston]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Green|first1=Alex|title=How Forrest Preston built Life Care Centers into the biggest privately held company in the industry|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/business/aroundregion/story/2015/apr/27/how-forrest-preston-built-life-care-centers-biggest-privately-held-company-industry/301066/|accessdate=September 13, 2015|work=timesfreepress|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> Jones previously lived in the [[Centenary Avenue Historic District]] in downtown Cleveland.<ref name=\"site3\"/>\n\nPolitically, Jones has been an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]], and has donated to the campaigns of both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians, but his views are characterized to be [[Right-wing politics|right-leaning]] and fiscally [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]. Jones supported [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. Presidential Election]]. A few days after the [[inauguration of President Trump]], Jones stated in an interview with [[Fox & Friends]] that he was \"tired of Presidents who were politicians\" and believed that small businesses would benefit from Trump's policies.<ref>{{cite AV media |people= |date=January 30, 2017|title=Allan Jones on Fox and Friends|trans-title= |medium= |language= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KnkntifOTGQ&t=11s|access-date= |format= |time= |location= |publisher=Fox News|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Toby McKenzie]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://wallanjones.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Allan}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bneu2013", "label": "safe", "comment": "consolidating duplicate references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Jones_(businessman)"}
{"title_page": "Idiot Wind", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br>[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018. Some reviewers have speculated that the song is a reflection on Dylan's personal life, and in particular on his deteriorating relationship with his wife [[Sara Dylan]], whilst Dylan has denied that it is autobiographical.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from [[Sara Dylan]], who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2|pages=160\u2013}}</ref> and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt0HAQAAMAAJ|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that \"Idiot Wind\" was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem ''June 1940'' by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|pages=140\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included just guitar and bass, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind,\" in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of \"Idiot Wind\" featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u2013}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn't stop. It wouldn't stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It's something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" /><ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan's More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\"{{efn|Sara Dylan was known as Sara Lownds before marrying Bob Dylan}} O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> avid Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with \"Idiot Wind\" \u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played \"Idiot Wind\" in a show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" /> This live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref> and was also included on the Dylan album [[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]] that was released in Japan and Australia.<ref name=\"BJ762\" /><ref name=\"Bell2013\">{{cite book|author=Ian Bell|title=Time Out of Mind: The Lives of Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbx8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT614|date=12 September 2013|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-78057-835-4|pages=614\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan has denied that the song refers to his personal life. He told interviewer Bill Flanagan that although many people thought that \"Idiot Wind\" and the album ''Blood on the Tracks'' related to his life, \"It didn't pertain to me. It was just a concept of putting in images that defy time - yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wanted to make them all kind of connect in some kind of a strange way.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\" /> In his 2004 memoir ''[[Chronicles: Volume One]]'' Dylan claimed that ''Blood on the Tracks'' was \"an entire album based on [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] short stories. Critics thought it was autobiographical \u2013 that was fine.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and \"Idiot Wind\", which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We\u2019re idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of \"Idiot Wind\".\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan\u2019s Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|pages=257\u2013}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''[[The Guardian]]'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You\u2019re an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Live Performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992 when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that \"Idiot Wind\" was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of \"Idiot Wind\" are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] picked out \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in [[Conor McPherson]]'s play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original 2017 London production at [[The Old Vic]] and the subsequent transfer to the [[West End theatre|West End]] it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], playing the role of Marianne Laine, as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"McPherson2017\">{{cite book|author=Conor McPherson|title=Girl from the North Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2FhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT9|date=20 November 2017|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|isbn=978-1-55936-882-7|pages=9\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"RWG\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bano |first=Tim |title=Girl from the North Country star Sheila Atim: \u2018You don\u2019t want to be a freedom fighter every time you enter a job\u2019 |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |work=The Stage |date=15 January 2019 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Atim won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"BJ762\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Bell2013\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, vocals; [[Roger McGuinn]]: guitar, vocals; [[David Mansfield]]: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; [[Rob Stoner]]: bass; [[Howard Wyeth|Howie Wyeth]]: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || \n|-\n| 3 || ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' || 1978 || Hughes Stadium || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, Scarlet Rivera: violin; T-bone J. Henry Burnett: guitar, piano; Steven Soles: guitar; Mick Ronson: guitar; Bobby Neuwirth: guitar, vocals; Roger McGuinn: guitar, vocals; David Mansfield: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; Rob Stoner: bass; Howie Wyeth: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || Previously released on ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''. ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' was released in 1978 in Japan and Australia.\n|-\n| 4 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' || 1991 || [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]] || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) - with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass. Organ overdub by [[Paul Griffin]].<refname=\"Heylin2010\" /> || \n|-\n| 5 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' || 2018 || A&R Studios|| 19/09/1974 || 4 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 6 || rowspan=\"9\" | ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]] (Deluxe edition)'' || rowspan=\"9\" | 2018 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 1 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 7 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 1 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 8 ||  A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 3 (with insert) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 9 ||  A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 5 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 10 || A&R Studios || 16/09/1974 || 6 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 11 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || Rehearsal and Takes 1-3, Remake || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 12 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 13 || A&R Studios || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) - with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || Previously released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]''\n|-\n| 14 || Sound 80 || 27/12/1974 ||  || \"Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; Billy Peterson: bass; Bill Berg: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''\n|-\n| 15 || ''The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |title=The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country \u2013 Out Now |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=18 January 2018 |website=legacyrecordings.co.uk |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> || 2018 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |title=Bob Dylan's The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country announced |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=19 December 2017 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including \"Idiot Wind\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Covers of \"Idiot Wind\" were also included on [[Phil Pritchett]]'s album ''Blueprint Garage Volume 2''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deezer.com/en/track/77303011 |title=Idiot Wind: Phil Pritchett |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=deezer.com |publisher=Deezer |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original cast recording of ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]'', recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]], includes the song. As in the original London production of the play, it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"RWG\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/news/2017/08/the-girl-from-the-north-country-cast-recording |title=The Girl from the North Country cast recording is here |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 August 2017 |website=oldvictheatre.com |publisher=The Old Vic |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics to \"Idiot Wind\"]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br>[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018. Some reviewers have speculated that the song is a reflection on Dylan's personal life, and in particular on his deteriorating relationship with his wife [[Sara Dylan]], whilst Dylan has denied that it is autobiographical.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from [[Sara Dylan]], who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2|pages=160\u2013}}</ref> and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tt0HAQAAMAAJ|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that \"Idiot Wind\" was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem ''June 1940'' by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|pages=140\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included just guitar and bass, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind,\" in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u2013}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of \"Idiot Wind\" featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u2013}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn't stop. It wouldn't stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It's something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" /><ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan's More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\"{{efn|Sara Dylan was known as Sara Lownds before marrying Bob Dylan}} O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> avid Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with \"Idiot Wind\" \u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played \"Idiot Wind\" in a show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" /> This live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref> and was also included on the Dylan album [[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]] that was released in Japan and Australia.<ref name=\"BJ762\" /><ref name=\"Bell2013\">{{cite book|author=Ian Bell|title=Time Out of Mind: The Lives of Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbx8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT614|date=12 September 2013|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-78057-835-4|pages=614\u2013}}</ref>\n\nDylan has denied that the song refers to his personal life. He told interviewer Bill Flanagan that although many people thought that \"Idiot Wind\" and the album ''Blood on the Tracks'' related to his life, \"It didn't pertain to me. It was just a concept of putting in images that defy time - yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wanted to make them all kind of connect in some kind of a strange way.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\" /> In his 2004 memoir ''[[Chronicles: Volume One]]'' Dylan claimed that ''Blood on the Tracks'' was \"an entire album based on [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] short stories. Critics thought it was autobiographical \u2013 that was fine.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and \"Idiot Wind\", which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We\u2019re idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of \"Idiot Wind\".\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan\u2019s Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|pages=257\u2013}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''[[The Guardian]]'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You\u2019re an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Live Performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992 when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that \"Idiot Wind\" was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0|pages=129\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of \"Idiot Wind\" are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] picked out \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in [[Conor McPherson]]'s play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original 2017 London production at [[The Old Vic]] and the subsequent transfer to the [[West End theatre|West End]] it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], playing the role of Marianne Laine, as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"McPherson2017\">{{cite book|author=Conor McPherson|title=Girl from the North Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2FhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT9|date=20 November 2017|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|isbn=978-1-55936-882-7|pages=9\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"RWG\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bano |first=Tim |title=Girl from the North Country star Sheila Atim: \u2018You don\u2019t want to be a freedom fighter every time you enter a job\u2019 |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |work=The Stage |date=15 January 2019 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Atim won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"BJ762\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Bell2013\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, vocals; [[Roger McGuinn]]: guitar, vocals; [[David Mansfield]]: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; [[Rob Stoner]]: bass; [[Howard Wyeth|Howie Wyeth]]: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || \n|-\n| 3 || ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' || 1978 || Hughes Stadium || 23/05/1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, Scarlet Rivera: violin; T-bone J. Henry Burnett: guitar, piano; Steven Soles: guitar; Mick Ronson: guitar; Bobby Neuwirth: guitar, vocals; Roger McGuinn: guitar, vocals; David Mansfield: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; Rob Stoner: bass; Howie Wyeth: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || Previously released on ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''. ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' was released in 1978 in Japan and Australia.\n|-\n| 4 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' || 1991 || [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]] || 19/09/1974 || 4 (remake) - with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bas