ate=7 April 2020}}</ref> || 2018 || [[Sound 80]] || 27/12/1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |title=Bob Dylan\u2019s The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country announced |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=19 December 2017 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including \"Idiot Wind\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Covers of \"Idiot Wind\" were also included on [[Phil Pritchett]]'s album ''Blueprint Garage Volume 2''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deezer.com/en/track/77303011 |title=Idiot Wind: Phil Pritchett |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=deezer.com |publisher=Deezer |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original cast recording of ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]'', recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]], includes the song. As in the original London production of the play, it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"RWG\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/news/2017/08/the-girl-from-the-north-country-cast-recording |title=The Girl from the North Country cast recording is here |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 August 2017 |website=oldvictheatre.com |publisher=The Old Vic |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics to \"Idiot Wind\"]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "name_user": "BennyOnTheLoose", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idiot_Wind"}
{"title_page": "Sam Bradford", "text_new": "{{Short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{About|the quarterback|musician|Sam Bradford (musician)}}{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name = Sam Bradford\n|image = Rams quarterback Sam Bradford at the coaching clinic.jpg\n|caption = Bradford in 2012\n|currentteam = Free agent \n|number = \n|position = [[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|11|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]]\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|height_ft =  6\n|height_in =  4\n|weight_lbs =  224\n|high_school = [[Putnam City North High School|Oklahoma City (OK) Putnam City North]]\n|college = [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]]\n|draftyear = 2010\n|draftround = 1\n|draftpick = [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|1]]\n|pastteams =\n* [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2016}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2017}})\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2018}})\n|status=\n|highlights =\n* [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] (2010)\n* [[List of National Football League annual pass completion percentage leaders|NFL completion percentage leader]] (2016)\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2008)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (2008)\n* [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year|Associated Press Player of the Year]] (2008)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' Player of the Year]] (2008)\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2008 College Football All-America Team|2008]])\n* [[Big 12 Conference football individual awards|Big 12 Offensive Player of the Year]] (2008)\n* First-team All-[[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] ([[2008 All-Big 12 Conference football team|2008]])\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2018\n|statlabel1=Passing attempts\n|statvalue1=2,967\n|statlabel2=Passing completions\n|statvalue2=1,855\n|statlabel3=Percentage\n|statvalue3=62.5\n|statlabel4=[[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n|statvalue4=103\u201361\n|statlabel5=Passing yards\n|statvalue5=19,449\n|statlabel6=[[Passer rating]]\n|statvalue6=84.5\n| nflnew = sambradford/497095\n}}\n'''Samuel Jacob Bradford''' (born November 8, 1987) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who is a free agent. He has played in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for the [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]], [[Philadelphia Eagles]], [[Minnesota Vikings]], and [[Arizona Cardinals]]. Bradford attended [[Putnam City North High School]] in [[Oklahoma City]], where he starred in football, basketball and golf. As a senior quarterback in 2005, he threw for 2,029 yards and 17 touchdowns in 12 games. Bradford was not highly recruited coming out of high school, but he did receive a scholarship offer from the [[University of Oklahoma]], which he accepted. After a redshirt season in 2006, Bradford threw for 3,121 yards and 36 touchdowns as a redshirt freshman. In 2008, Bradford became only the second sophomore to win the [[Heisman Trophy]] as he led the highest-scoring offense in NCAA history, throwing for 4,720 yards with 50 touchdowns and just eight interceptions. He again led the nation in passing and also added five rushing touchdowns as the Sooners went 12-1 and advanced to the BCS national title game.\n\nBradford declared for the NFL Draft following the 2009 season and was drafted by the [[St. Louis Rams]] with the [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall]] selection in the [[2010 NFL Draft]]. That year, Bradford set the record for most completions by a rookie in NFL history, which helped earn him the [[NFL Offensive Rookie of the Year]] award. Prior to the start of the 2015 season, the Rams traded Bradford along with a 2015 fifth round pick to the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] in exchange for quarterback [[Nick Foles]], a 2015 fourth-round pick, and a 2016 second-round pick. Following his 2015 campaign with the Eagles, in which he set career-highs in passing yards (3,725), completion percentage (65%) and yards per attempt (7.0), the [[Minnesota Vikings]] acquired Bradford after their starting quarterback [[Teddy Bridgewater]] was lost to a season-ending knee injury before the start of the season.\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\n==Early years==\nBradford was born to Kent and Martha Bradford in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]].<ref name=\"soonersports.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/football-depth-chart.html |title=Official Site of the Oklahoma Sooners |publisher=SoonerSports.com |date=September 22, 2010 |access-date=September 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925221001/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/football-depth-chart.html |archive-date=September 25, 2010 |df= }}</ref>  He attended [[Putnam City North High School]] in Oklahoma City, where he starred in [[high school football|football]], basketball, baseball, and golf for the Putnam City North Panthers.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.twincities.com/2016/09/24/vikings-qb-sam-bradford-was-an-all-everything-athlete-until-football-won-out/ |title=Vikings QB Sam Bradford was an all-everything athlete until football won out |date=September 24, 2016 |work=Twin Cities |access-date=January 25, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Bradford played as a [[pitcher]] in [[baseball]], but gave up after his freshman year. He earned All-City honors as a junior [[quarterback]] in [[high school football|football]] by ''The Oklahoman''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/2878373|title=The Oklahoman's Big All-City Football team: Roster and player profiles|date=December 19, 2004|website=newsok.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Following his senior season in which he threw for 2,029 yards and 17 touchdowns in 12 games, Bradford was named to the Oklahoma Coaches Association All-State Team and was a Second-Team All-State pick by ''[[The Oklahoman]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/2891825|title=BOYS ALL-STATE ROSTER|date=April 10, 2005|website=newsok.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SS_Bio\">{{cite web | title=14 Sam Bradford | publisher=SoonerSports.com | url=http://soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/bradford_sam00.html | accessdate=September 11, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nBradford was also a Division I-caliber [[basketball]] player. As a senior, he averaged 18.6 points and 10.5 rebounds per game and played on the same elite [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] team as fellow Oklahoma City native and [[Detroit Pistons]] star [[Blake Griffin]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/columns/story?columnist=maisel_ivan&id=3134076|title=Oklahoma's rookie QB makes college game looks easy|publisher=ES-28PN|accessdate=November 30, 2007|date=November 30, 2007|first=Ivan|last=Maisel}}</ref> In [[golf]], Bradford defeated future [[PGA Tour|PGA]] touring pros [[Kevin Tway]] and [[Robert Streb]] during his high school career. In addition to the aforementioned sports, Bradford also played [[hockey]] in his youth. In 1999, when Bradford was 12, his travel team, the Junior Blazers, won a regional championship, beating a team from Houston. He quit the sport that same year, and according to his former hockey coach [[Mike McEwen (ice hockey)|Mike McEwen]], who played on three [[Stanley Cup]] championship teams with the [[New York Islanders]], Bradford had the talent to make it in the [[National Hockey League|NHL]]. McEwen also said that Bradford was one of the best players he ever coached.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/eagles/Sam_Bradford_Eagles_All_American_everything.html|title=Sam Bradford: All-American everything|website=philly.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2005, by the end of Bradford's junior season, he garnered interest from several Division I programs, including [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]], [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]], [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]], and nearby Oklahoma. Following his senior season, Bradford was viewed as a two-to-three-star recruit and was not that highly ranked among the high school class of 2006, with his highest ranking being No. 12 among only pro-style quarterbacks by recruiting source ''[[Rivals.com]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Pete |last=Thamel |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Bradford Wins Heisman, but the Top Prize Awaits |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/14/sports/ncaafootball/14heisman.html |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date=December 13, 2008 |accessdate= }}</ref> Bradford was ranked behind [[Pat Devlin (American football)|Pat Devlin]], [[Isiah Williams|\"Juice\" Williams]] and [[Josh Freeman]], and was overshadowed by the likes of five-star recruits like [[Mitch Mustain]], [[Matthew Stafford]] and [[Tim Tebow]].<ref name=\"SS_Bio\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=9&c=4&pid=10&yr=2006 | title=Football Recruiting \u2013 Quarterback | accessdate=September 11, 2007 | publisher=Scout.com }}</ref>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2006}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Sam Bradford\n| position = [[Quarterback|QB]]\n| hometown = Oklahoma City, Oklahoma\n| highschool = [[Putnam City North High School]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 4\n| weight = 200\n| 40     = 4.78\n| commitdate = December 2, 2005\n| scout stars  = 3\n| rivals stars = 3\n| espn grade = 79\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               = yes\n| year             = 2006\n| rivals ref title = 2006 Oklahoma Football Commitment List\n| scout ref title  = 2006 Oklahoma College Football Recruiting Commits\n| espn ref title   =\n| rivals school    = oklahoma\n| scout s          = 146\n| espn schoolid    =\n| scout overall    = 18 ([[Quarterback|QB]])\n| rivals overall   = 12 (QB), 1 (Oklahoma)\n| espn overall     = 16 (QB)\n| accessdate       = September 21, 2016\n}}\n\n==College career==\nBradford received an [[athletic scholarship]] to attend the [[University of Oklahoma]], where he played for coach [[Bob Stoops]]'s [[Oklahoma Sooners football]] team from 2006 to 2009. He redshirted as a freshman in 2006 before becoming the starter in 2007 and turning in one of the best seasons ever by a quarterback, passing for 4,720 yards with 50 touchdowns and just eight interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/sam-bradford-1/gamelog/2008/ |title=Sam Bradford 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> As a result, he won the [[Heisman Trophy]], becoming the fifth Oklahoma player to win the award. After Oklahoma lost the [[2009 BCS National Championship Game]] 24-14 to [[Florida Gators|Florida]], Bradford, instead of declaring for the upcoming draft, elected to return to Oklahoma for another crack at the title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-01-08-florida.html |title=BCS Championship - Oklahoma vs Florida Box Score, January 8, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> He ended up playing in just three games due to a shoulder injury, and the Sooners, ranked No. 3 to start the season, finished with an 8-5 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/2009.html |title=2009 Oklahoma Sooners Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Freshman season===\n{{See also|2006 Oklahoma Sooners football team}}\nIn 2006, Oklahoma's starting quarterback [[Rhett Bomar]], then a sophomore, was dismissed from the team for violating [[NCAA]] rules.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/2824545 |title=Bomar, Quinn dismissed from OU football team |date=August 3, 2006 |website=NewsOK.com |language=en-US |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Paul Thompson (American football)|Paul Thompson]], a senior quarterback-turned-wide receiver, converted back to quarterback and led the [[2006 Oklahoma Sooners football team]] to win the [[Big 12 Championship Game]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/2006.html |title=2006 Oklahoma Sooners Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/2006-schedule.html |title=2006 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> His departure left a void at the quarterback position at Oklahoma. Six players on the roster tried out for the starting position during the following off-season, including three [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] quarterbacks,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfbstats.com/2007/team/522/roster.html|title=2007 Oklahoma Sooners Roster}}</ref> [[true freshman]] Keith Nichol (a [[Rivals.com]] 4-star recruit and 6th-ranked dual-threat quarterback in the 2007 recruiting class, who later transferred to [[Michigan State University]]), junior Joey Halzle (the only one with game experience), and Bradford, a [[redshirt freshman]]. On August 21, 2007, Bradford won the starting quarterback role for the [[2007 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2007 team]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/082107aaa.html | publisher=SoonerSports.com | title=Bradford Gets Nod at Quarterback | access-date=August 21, 2007 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007165746/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/082107aaa.html | archive-date=October 7, 2007 | df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:OUSoonersQBs-April2007.jpg|thumb|left|Bradford (left), Joey Halzle (center), and Hays McEachern (right) during spring practice in April 2007]]\n\nIn his first game for the Sooners, against the [[University of North Texas]], Bradford completed 21 of 23&nbsp;attempts for 363&nbsp;yards and three touchdowns in a little over two quarters, breaking the school record for passing yards in a half, held by his quarterback coach [[Josh Heupel]], with 350.<ref name=\"Sooner newbies\">{{cite news | title=Sooner newbies Bradford, Murray debut with monster games | first=Jenni | last=Carlson | publisher=NewsOK.com | url=http://newsok.com/article/3116419 | accessdate=September 4, 2007 | date=September 2, 2007 }}</ref> The very next game, Bradford broke [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Jason White (American football)|Jason White]]'s school record for most consecutive pass completions with 22 (18 came in the first half and four at the start of the second).<ref name=\"NOK1_OUUM\">{{cite news | title=Sooners' Bradford proves that he belongs | publisher=NewsOK.com | first=Jake | last=Trotter | url=http://newsok.com/article/3121288 | date=September 9, 2007 | accessdate=September 10, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the second week of the 2007 season, Bradford was named the national offensive player of the week by the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Bradford Captures Camp Honor | url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090907aab.html | publisher=SoonerSports.com | access-date=September 10, 2007 | date=September 9, 2007 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204060416/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090907aab.html | archive-date=December 4, 2008 | df= }}</ref> after tying the school record for most touchdown passes in a game with five.<ref>{{cite web | title=Oklahoma Rocks Miami, 51\u201313 | url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090807aaa.html | publisher=SoonerSports.com | access-date=September 10, 2007 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013141054/http://soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/recaps/090807aaa.html | archive-date=October 13, 2007 | df= }}</ref> Having thrown 25 touchdowns through his first nine games, Bradford was on pace to break the [[NCAA]] freshman record of 29&nbsp;touchdowns set by [[David Neill]] in 1998 and tied by [[Colt McCoy]] in 2006.\n\nIn the November 17, 2007 game against [[Texas Tech Red Raiders|Texas Tech]], Bradford suffered a concussion of unknown severity. He was removed from the game and replaced by back-up quarterback Joey Halzle. The Sooners lost the game, 27\u201334.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Sports Network I-A College Football | url = http://www.sportsnetwork.com/default.asp?c=sportsnetwork&page=/cfoot/news/AFN4113246.htm | publisher = The Sports Network | accessdate = November 18, 2007}}</ref> Bradford was able to play in the [[Bedlam Series|Bedlam]] game against [[Oklahoma State Cowboys|Oklahoma State]] on November 24.<ref>{{cite web | title = ESPN \u2013 Sooners QB Bradford to be reevaluated this week \u2013 College Football | url = http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3117799 | publisher = ESPN | accessdate = November 21, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsline.com/collegefootball/story/11118296|title=Bradford's early exit in '07 means Tech still has to size up Sam|website=sportsline.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the November 24, 2007 game against the [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State Cowboys]], Bradford broke the NCAA freshman record of 29 touchdowns by passing his 30th touchdown to [[Joe Jon Finley]] during the second quarter.<ref>{{cite news | title=Patrick runs for career-best 202 yards, 2 TDs as OU rolls | publisher=ESPN | accessdate=November 24, 2007 | date=November 24, 2007 | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=273280201 }}</ref> At the [[Missouri Tigers]] game, Bradford threw for 209&nbsp;yards and 0&nbsp;interceptions. He was 18\u201326 and threw for two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-10-13-oklahoma.html |title=Missouri at Oklahoma Box Score, October 13, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Sooners won the [[Big 12 Championship Game|Big 12 Championship]] after defeating Missouri for the second time in a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2007-12-01-missouri.html |title=Oklahoma vs Missouri Box Score, December 1, 2007 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The Sooners played the [[West Virginia Mountaineers]] in the [[Fiesta Bowl]] on January 2, 2008 and lost 48\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-01-02-oklahoma.html |title=Fiesta Bowl - West Virginia vs Oklahoma Box Score, January 2, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> It was Bradford's first [[Bowl Championship Series]] game as a starter.\n\n===Sophomore season===\n{{See also|2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team}}\n[[File:OklahomaSooners-SamBradford (cropped 1).jpg|thumb|180 px|Sam Bradford during the 2008 NCAA season.]]\nIn week 8 of the following season against [[2008 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]], Bradford surpassed quarterback coach [[Josh Heupel]]'s school record for passing yards in a single game with 468 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://newsok.com/article/3313297 |title=Jenni Carlson exclusive: Bradford blossoms under Heupel's helping hand |date=October 19, 2008 |website=NewsOK.com |language=en-US |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Bradford led the Sooners to their third straight Big 12 Championship and defeated Missouri 62\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-12-06-missouri.html |title=Oklahoma vs Missouri Box Score, December 6, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In the process, the Sooners broke Hawaii's 2006 record for the most points in a single season with 702 points. Also, the Sooners were the first team in NCAA history to score 60 or more points in five straight games. Oklahoma finished the 2008 regular season with a 12\u20131 record, ranking #2 in the AP Poll and #1 in the BCS Standings.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/2008.html |title=2008 Oklahoma Sooners Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The Sooners earned a trip to play [[University of Florida|Florida]] at the [[2009 BCS National Championship Game]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-01-08-florida.html |title=BCS Championship - Oklahoma vs Florida Box Score, January 8, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the regular season, Bradford captured the [[Davey O'Brien Award]]<ref name=OBrien08>{{cite news|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/sports/article.aspx?subjectid=92&articleid=20081212_92_B1_Olhmur200895|title=Bradford is winner of O'Brien QB award}}</ref> and the [[Heisman Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heisman.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121308aaa.html|title=SAM BRADFORD OF THE UNIVERSITY OF OKLAHOMA SELECTED AS THE 2008 HEISMAN WINNER|website=heisman.com|access-date=May 23, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217034536/http://www.heisman.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121308aaa.html|archive-date=December 17, 2008|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsok.com/heisman-u-sam-bradford-is-latest-in-impressive-r-ou-q/article/3328676?custom_click=lead_story_title|title=Heisman U? Sam Bradford is latest in impressive run of OU signal-callers}}</ref> He is the second sophomore, after 2007 winner [[Tim Tebow]] of the University of Florida, to receive the Heisman; he also became the fifth University of Oklahoma player, as well as the second person of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] descent to capture the trophy after Jim Plunkett.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsnetwork.com/merge/tsnform.aspx?c=sportsnetwork&page=cfoot/news/news.aspx?id=4197477|title= Bradford wins 2008 Heisman Trophy}}</ref> Bradford received 1,726 total points while the other finalists, [[Colt McCoy]], of the University of Texas, and Tim Tebow, received 1,604 and 1,575, respectively. Tebow, however, collected more first-place votes, 309, while Bradford got 300. Bradford got the most points thanks to the help of his 315 second-place votes. A total of 926 voters participated in the balloting.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/sports/article.aspx?subjectid=92&articleid=20081213_297_0_NWYRut498164|title=OU's Sam Bradford wins 74th Heisman Trophy}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+2008 Heisman Trophy Finalist Voting<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/hotstories/6163533.html|title=Oklahoma QB Bradford wins Heisman Trophy}}</ref>\n! Finalist\n! First place votes<br />(3 pts. each)\n! Second place votes<br />(2 pts. each)\n! Third place votes<br />(1 pt. each)\n! Total points\n|-\n| Sam Bradford\n| 300\n| 315\n| 196\n| 1,726\n|-\n| [[Colt McCoy]]\n| 266\n| 288\n| 230\n| 1,604\n|-\n| [[Tim Tebow]]\n| 309\n| 207\n| 234\n| 1,575\n|}\n\nWhen combined with [[Blake Griffin]]'s [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith Award]], [[Oklahoma Sooners|Oklahoma]] became the first school to have a winner in both top basketball and football individual awards in the same year. Bradford was also voted [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year]]. Bradford received 27 votes, again beating McCoy (17 votes) and Tim Tebow (16 votes).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=ap-applayeroftheyear&prov=ap&type=lgns|title=NCAAF on Yahoo! Sports - News, Scores, Standings, Rumors, Fantasy Games|website=Yahoo Sports|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Bradford is the third Oklahoma Sooner to win the award, joining [[Josh Heupel]] (2000) and [[Jason White (American football)|Jason White]] (2003). Heupel and White were also quarterbacks, with Heupel being the current quarterbacks coach for Oklahoma.\n\nBradford faced [[2008 Florida Gators football team|Florida]], led by Tebow, in the [[2009 BCS National Championship Game]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/printedition/la-sp-dufresne5-2009jan05,0,6538839.column|title=\nSam Bradford and Tim Tebow are Heismans apart | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Chris | last=Dufresne | date=January 5, 2009 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref> He threw 26-of-41 passes for 256 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions, as Florida won the game 24\u201314.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=290080201|title=Florida Gators vs. Oklahoma Sooners Box Score, January 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\n{{See also|2009 Oklahoma Sooners football team}}\nBradford announced that he would forgo the [[2009 NFL Draft]] to return to Oklahoma for his junior season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/ncaa/01/14/bradford.ap/index.html |title=Sam Bradford Will Return to Oklahoma |publisher=SI.com |date=January 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090121141013/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/ncaa/01/14/bradford.ap/index.html |archive-date=January 21, 2009 }}</ref> In the Sooners' first game of the season (against [[2009 BYU Cougars football team|Brigham Young]]), Bradford suffered a third-degree [[AC joint]] sprain one play after becoming Oklahoma's all-time passing leader. Playing without Bradford for the second half of the game, Oklahoma went on to lose 14\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=292480201|title=BYU vs. Oklahoma - Game Recap - September 5, 2009 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Bradford was originally scheduled to return in about three to six weeks,<ref name=\"Hall's TD\">{{cite news | title=Hall's TD pass with 3:03 remaining lifts Cougars over No. 3 Sooners | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=292480201 | agency=Associated Press | publisher=ESPN.com | date=September 5, 2009 | accessdate=September 5, 2009}}</ref> but head coach Bob Stoops initially refused to either confirm or deny that timetable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsok.com/ous-bob-stoops-sam-bradford-still-questionable-for-miami/article/3402852 |title=OU's Bob Stoops: Sam Bradford still questionable for Miami |newspaper=The Oklahoman |first=Mike |last=Baldwin |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=December 19, 2010}}</ref> After missing three weeks, Bradford returned to the field during the [[2009 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]] game, and completed 27 of 49 passes for 389 yards and one touchdown, leading the Sooners to a 33\u20137 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.omaha.com/article/20091010/SPORTS/710109763|title=Big 12: Even with Bradford, Sooners beatable}}</ref> Bradford re-injured his right shoulder on October 17, 2009 in the [[Red River Rivalry]] against [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] on the second drive of the game. It was later announced that he would undergo season-ending shoulder surgery and enter the [[2010 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rivals.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=ap-t25-oklahoma-bradford&prov=ap&type=lgns |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5l2ZsTqU9?url=http://rivals.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news?slug=ap-t25-oklahoma-bradford&prov=ap&type=lgns |archive-date=November 4, 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* 2007 ''[[Sporting News]]'' Freshman of the Year<ref name=TSN07>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/exclusives/20071207/971576-p.html|title=SN's 2007 college football All-Americans|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212012610/http://www.sportingnews.com/exclusives/20071207/971576-p.html|archive-date=December 12, 2007|df=}}</ref>\n* 2007 Second-team All-American by ''Sporting News''<ref name=TSN07/>\n* 2007 Honorable mention All-American by ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.profootballweekly.com/PFW/College+Football/College+Football+Extras/2007/allamerica.htm|title=Nolan Nawrocki\u2019s All-America team}}</ref> ''College Football News'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cfn.scout.com/2/710932.html|title=2007 CFN All-America Teams|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091220212854/http://cfn.scout.com/2/710932.html|archive-date=December 20, 2009|df=}}</ref> and ''Sports Illustrated''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/football/ncaa/12/10/all.americas/index.html|title=SI.com's 2007 All-Americas | work=CNN | date=December 11, 2007 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2007 All-[[Big 12]] honorable mention by the league's coaches<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=106181&SPID=13139&DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=1522092|title=2007 All-Big 12 Football Awards Announced}}</ref>\n* 2007 All-Big 12 Academic Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/fls/10410/oldsite/photos/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07_AAB12_TEAM.pdf?SPSID=106181&SPID=13139&DB_OEM_ID=10410|title=2007 Academic All-Big 12 Football Team Announced}}</ref>\n* 2008 Second-team Academic All-American by ''[[ESPN The Magazine]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivyleaguesports.com/documents/08CoSIDAAAA(FB).pdf|title=2008 ESPN THE MAGAZINE Academic All-America}}</ref>\n* 2008 All-Big 12 Academic Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/pdf5/353968.pdf?ATCLID=3623034&SPSID=106181&SPID=13139&DB_OEM_ID=10410|title=2008 Academic All-Big 12 Football Team Announced}}</ref>\n* 2008 Big 12 Offensive Player of the Year as named by the league's coaches, who also selected him to the All-Big 12 first team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=3626465|title=2008 All-Big 12 Football Awards Announced}}</ref>\n* 2008 First-team [[2008 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] by [[CBS Sports]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsline.com/collegefootball/story/11167903|title=CBSSports.com 2008 All-America Team|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215095643/http://www.sportsline.com/collegefootball/story/11167903|archive-date=December 15, 2008|df=}}</ref> [[Rivals.com]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=887528|title=Rivals.com 2008 All-America Teams|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081211021347/http://collegefootball.rivals.com/content.asp?CID=887528|archive-date=December 11, 2008|df=}}</ref> [[ESPN]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/flash/2008/allamerican|title=2008 ESPN All-Americans}}</ref> [[Associated Press]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ncaafootball.com/index.php?s=&url_channel_id=34&url_article_id=15445&change_well_id=2|title=Associated Press names 2008 All-America Team}}</ref> and ''Sporting News''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=497803|title=Sporting News' college football All-American First Team|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221073122/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=497803|archive-date=December 21, 2008|df=}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Davey O'Brien Award]] winner<ref name=OBrien08/>\n* 2008 [[Heisman Trophy]] winner<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/12/AR2008121203921.html|title=Heisman Finalists | work=The Washington Post | date=December 13, 2008 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year Award|Associated Press College Football Player of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=6510947|title=AP College Football Player of the Year Winner}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Sammy Baugh Trophy]]\n* 2008 co-[[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' Player of the Year]]<ref>{{cite news\n |url         = http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2008/12/texas-tech-qb-harrell-named-co-national.html\n |title       = Texas Tech QB Harrell named co-national player of the year\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20100118050035/http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2008/12/texas-tech-qb-harrell-named-co-national.html\n |archive-date = January 18, 2010\n |df          =\n}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Chic Harley Award|Harley Award]] <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.touchdownclubofcolumbus.com/Awards.htm|title=Touchdown Club News, Awards|date=March 27, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5yx70RPjP?url=http://www.touchdownclubofcolumbus.com/Awards.htm|archive-date=May 25, 2011|df=}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Touchdown Club of Columbus#Quarterback of the Year|Touchdown Club of Columbus Quarterback of the Year]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.touchdownclubofcolumbus.com/PastHonorees.htm | title=NCAA Quarterback of the Year | work=Touchdown Club of Columbus | date=April 6, 2009 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121205081717/http://www.touchdownclubofcolumbus.com/PastHonorees.htm | archive-date=December 5, 2012 | df= }}</ref>\n}}\n* 2010 [[NFL Draft]] First overall pick\n* 2010 Carroll Rosenbloom Memorial Award (St. Louis Rams' rookie of the year award)\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Rushing\n|-\n! Season !! Team !! {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] || [[2007 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| 14 || 237 || 341  || 69.5 || 3,121 || 36 || 8 || 176.52 || 31 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] || [[2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| 14 || 328 || 483 || 67.9 || 4,721 || 50 || 8 || 180.86 || 42 || 47 || 5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] || [[2009 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]]\n| 3 || 39 || 69 || 56.5 || 562 || 2 || 0 || 134.5 || 4 || \u221218 || 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| colspan=2 | '''Career''' || 31 || 604 || 893 || 67.6 || 8,403 || 88 || 16 || 175.6 || 77 || 36 || 5\n|}\n\n''Source'':<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/sam-bradford-1.html|title=Sam Bradford}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Pre-draft===\nAlthough he likely would have been one of the first quarterbacks taken in the [[2009 NFL Draft]], Bradford decided to return to Oklahoma for his junior season in January 2009.<ref>{{Citation |last= |first= |date=January 14, 2009 |title=Sam Bradford announces he'll return to Sooners |newspaper=The Sporting News |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/college-football/article/2009-01-14/sam-bradford-announces-hell-return-sooners }}</ref> Shortly after the 2009 draft, he was projected as the No. 1 prospect for the [[2010 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/andrew_perloff/04/28/2010/index.html |first=Andrew |last=Perloff |date=April 28, 2009 |title=(Way early) 2010 NFL Mock Draft |work=SI.com }}</ref> On October 25, 2009, Bradford announced he would forgo his final year at Oklahoma and enter the draft.<ref name=\"EvansNYT\">{{Citation |last=Evans |first=Thayer |date=October 26, 2009 |title=Oklahoma\u2019s Bradford Chooses Season-Ending Surgery and Will Try for Draft |newspaper=New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/26/sports/ncaafootball/26bradford.html }}</ref> Commonly considered one of the top prospects available, Bradford was projected as high as the No. 1 overall pick for most of the preseason and the early part of the regular season.<ref name=\"McShayESPN\">{{cite news |first=Todd |last=McShay |authorlink=Todd McShay |title=QBs Sam Bradford and Colt McCoy are high in Todd McShay's early 2010 mock draft |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/nfl/draft09/insider/columns/story?columnist=mcshay_todd&id=4110478&action=upsell&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fnfl%2fdraft09%2finsider%2fcolumns%2fstory%3fcolumnist%3dmcshay_todd%26id%3d4110478 |work=ESPN.com |publisher= |date=April 30, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=\"PerloffSI\">{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Perloff |title=Sam Bradford goes No.1 to St. Louis Rams in 2010 NFL Mock Draft |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/andrew_perloff/04/28/2010/index.html |work=Sports Illustrated |publisher= |date=April 28, 2009 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref name=\"RangCBS\">{{Citation |last=Rang |first=Rob |date=October 23, 2009 |title=2009 NFL Mock Draft |work=CBSSports.com |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/nfldraftscout-RobRang }}</ref>\n\nBecause of his shoulder injury, Bradford did not throw at the 2010 [[NFL Combine]], however he was measured and participated in interviews and medical examinations. He was measured at 6'4\u00bc\" and 236 pounds, about 15 pounds above his college playing weight.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jeremiah |first=Daniel |date=February 26, 2009 |title=Oklahoma QB Sam Bradford measured at 6'4{{frac|1|4}}, 236 pounds at Friday's weigh-in |work=Rotoworld.com |url=http://www.rotoworld.com/content/playerpages/player_main.aspx?sport=NFL&id=5161}}</ref> Bradford scored 36 out of 50 on the [[Wonderlic test]], well above the average of 28.5 for the 30 NFL quarterbacks slated to start in 2010.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/wonderlic-scores-of-2010-nfl-starting-quarterbacks-and-339905.html |title=Wonderlic scores of 2010 NFL starting quarterbacks and NFL draft QB prospects |newspaper=[[Palm Beach Post]] |date=March 10, 2010 |first=Edgar |last=Thompson }}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Bradford met with [[St. Louis Rams]] general manager [[Billy Devaney]] and offensive coordinator [[Pat Shurmur]] in [[Pensacola, Florida]], where he had been training and rehabbing since undergoing surgery on his throwing shoulder.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/sports/stories.nsf/rams/story/A94CC5B1861CBED0862576EB000DE5E4?OpenDocument |title=Rams meet with Sam Bradford |first=Jim |last=Thomas |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=March 19, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n{{ external media\n| video1 = [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x151j33_sam-bradford-at-the-nfl-combine_sport Sam Bradford at the NFL Combine]\n| video2 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/09000d5d817b5576/Rams-take-Sam-Bradford Bradford gets drafted by St. Louis]\n}}\n\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 4\u00bc\n|       weight = 236\n|         dash = 4.70\n|    ten split =\n| twenty split =\n|      shuttle =\n|   cone drill =\n|     vertical =\n|     broad ft =\n|     broad in =\n|        bench =\n|    wonderlic = 36\n|     arm span = 34\u215c\n|    hand span = 9\u00bd\n|         note = All values from NFL Combine<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/sam-bradford?id=497095 |title=Sam Bradford Combine Profile |work=NFL.com |accessdate=February 27, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=64631&draftyear=2010&genpos=QB|title=Sam Bradford, DS #1 QB, Oklahoma|accessdate=November 8, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===St. Louis Rams===\n\n====2010 season====\n\nIn early Spring, Bradford met with Thom Goudy, a professional development coach in St. Louis, Missouri. Goudy helped Bradford with his pocket technique. Bradford spent three weeks in his training camp before starting the summer conditioning camp.\nOn April 22, 2010, Bradford was selected by the [[St. Louis Rams]] as the [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall pick]] in the [[2010 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://interact.stltoday.com/blogzone/around-the-horns/around-the-horns/2010/04/its-finally-official-rams-take-bradford |title=It's finally official: Rams take Bradford |publisher=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |date=April 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425055817/http://interact.stltoday.com/blogzone/around-the-horns/around-the-horns/2010/04/its-finally-official-rams-take-bradford |archive-date=April 25, 2010 |df= }}</ref> It was the first time the Rams selected a quarterback in the first round of a draft since the selection of [[Bill Munson]] in the [[1964 NFL Draft]]. Bradford is the first No. 1 pick out of Oklahoma since [[Billy Sims]] was selected top overall by the [[Detroit Lions]] in the [[1980 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/schools/oklahoma/drafted.htm |title=Oklahoma Drafted Players/Alumni |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Bradford chose the #8 in honor to [[Troy Aikman]] who also attended Oklahoma before transferring to UCLA.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/thehuddle/post/2010/04/rams-qb-sam-bradford-to-wear-no-8-as-homage-to-troy-aikman/1 |title=Bradford changes jersey number to honor Aikman |publisher=[[USA Today]] |date=April 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2010, Bradford signed a six-year, $78 million deal, which has $50 million of guarantees and has a maximum value of $86 million making it the largest contract ever for an NFL rookie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasyknuckleheads.com/breaking-st-louis-rams-sign-sam-bradford/|title=BREAKING: St. Louis Rams Sign Sam Bradford|website=fantasyknuckleheads.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/news/story?id=5425041 |first=Adam |last=Schefter |title=Bradford, Rams Agree On Record-Breaking Deal |publisher=ESPN.com news services |date=July 31, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn the preseason opener against the [[Minnesota Vikings]] on August 14, Bradford went 6-of-13 for 57 yards and was also sacked 3 times in a Rams loss.<ref>{{cite news |author=Mortensen, Chris |title=Sam Bradford not pressing to start |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nfl/trainingcamp10/columns/story?columnist=mortensen_chris&id=5464360 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=August 15, 2010 |accessdate=August 15, 2010}}</ref> After another unimpressive showing against the Browns in his second game, Bradford bounced back in a big way against the Patriots in the third game of the preseason. He got his first start in place of the injured [[A. J. Feeley]], throwing two first half touchdowns and helping lead the Rams to a 36\u201335 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010082652/2010/PRE3/rams@patriots#menu=gameinfo |title=Watch St. Louis Rams vs. New England Patriots [08/26/2010] - NFL.com |website=www.nfl.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe competed for the starting quarterback position with Feeley and on September 4, Bradford was named the starting quarterback for the 2010 season opener.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://views.washingtonpost.com/theleague/nflnewsfeed/2010/09/sam-bradford-named-rams-starter.html |title=Sam Bradford named Rams' starter|publisher=Washington Post |first=Mark |last=Maske| date=September 4, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn September 12, 2010, in his first regular season game as the starting quarterback for the Rams, Bradford completed 32/55 passes for 253 yards, 1 touchdown and 3 interceptions in a 17\u201313 loss to the [[Arizona Cardinals]]. His first NFL touchdown came on a 1-yard pass to [[Laurent Robinson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009120ram.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at St. Louis Rams - September 12th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Two weeks later, he then achieved his first victory as an NFL starter when the Rams defeated the [[Washington Redskins]] in an upset by a score of 30\u201316, which snapped a 13-game overall home losing streak.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009260ram.htm |title=Washington Redskins at St. Louis Rams - September 26th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The next week, he passed for 289 yards and two touchdowns in leading the Rams over the Seahawks, 20-3. This was their first win in a division game since November 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010030ram.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at St. Louis Rams - October 3rd, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 8 against the [[2010 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], Bradford connected on 25 of 32 passes, two of them for touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201010310ram.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at St. Louis Rams - October 31st, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In his first eight games, he scored eleven touchdowns, which tied an NFL record\u2014held by [[Dan Marino]] ({{NFL Year|1983}}), [[Peyton Manning]] ({{NFL Year|1998}}), and [[Ben Roethlisberger]] ({{NFL Year|2004}})\u2014for over that span by a rookie since the [[AFL\u2013NFL merger]] in 1970.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=301031014 |title=Rams at .500 as Sam Bradford tosses two TDs |work=ESPN.com |date=October 31, 2010 }}</ref> Bradford went 3-2 as a starter in October, passing for 1,019 yards and 7 touchdowns against 3 interceptions. He was named the NFL's offensive rookie of the month.\n\nDuring October and November, he established a record for most consecutive passes without an interception for a rookie (169), which ended with an interception by [[William Moore (American football)|William Moore]] in a home game against the [[2010 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] on November 21.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010112110/2010/REG11/falcons@rams |work=NFL.com |date=November 21, 2010 |title=NFL Game Center: Atlanta Falcons at St. Louis Rams - 2010 Week 11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120010747/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010112110/2010/REG11/falcons@rams |archive-date=November 20, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On November 28, 2010, against the [[Denver Broncos]], Bradford became the first rookie in NFL history to pass for at least 300 yards and three touchdowns with no interceptions during a road victory.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sando |first=Mike |date=November 29, 2010 |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nfcwest/post/_/id/28399/sam-bradfords-performance-in-perspective |title=Sam Bradford's performance in perspective |work=ESPN.com |accessdate=November 29, 2010 }}</ref> He capped November by becoming the first rookie quarterback to win two consecutive Offensive Rookie of the Month awards.\n\nOn December 26, Bradford surpassed [[Peyton Manning]]'s record for most completed passes by an NFL rookie quarterback (326). Bradford finished the season with 354 completions out of 590 attempts, surpassing Manning's record of 575 for most attempts by an NFL rookie quarterback. Bradford became just the third rookie quarterback to start all 16 regular season games and pass over 3,000 passing yards, joining [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.stltoday.com/sports/football/professional/article_581748de-673e-53f2-b505-335c5248d43d.html |title=The Rams' rock at quarterback |first=Jim |last=Thomas |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=December 30, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jan/01/sports/la-sp-nfl-sunday-spotlight-20110102 |title=Rams' Sam Bradford has displayed an unexpected quality: durability |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |first=Sam |last=Farmer |date=January 1, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BradSa00/gamelog/2010/ |title=Sam Bradford 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> He was named to the [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]], becoming the 5th Rams quarterback to claim this award, joining [[Neil Lomax]] (1981), [[Dieter Brock]] (1985), [[Jim Everett]] (1986), & [[Tony Banks (American football)|Tony Banks]]. \n\n====2011 season====\nComing into the 2011 season, expectations were high for the [[St. Louis Rams]] and Bradford. After going 4-0 in the preseason, it appeared as if they would be fulfilled, but once the regular season rolled around injuries ravaged the roster. A high ankle sprain bothered Bradford for the majority of the year and he finished with 2,164 passing yards, six touchdowns, and six interceptions. The team went 1\u20139 in games he appeared in and had a 2\u201314 record overall.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BradSa00/gamelog/2011/ |title=Sam Bradford 2011 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/2011.htm |title=2011 St. Louis Rams Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\nDuring the off-season, there was much speculation that the Rams would select [[Heisman Trophy]] winner and former [[Baylor Bears football|Baylor]] quarterback [[Robert Griffin III]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1428701-rgiii-vs-sam-bradford-why-st-louis-rams-made-the-wrong-decision-at-qb|title=RGIII vs. Sam Bradford: Why St. Louis Rams Made the Wrong Decision at QB|last=Collier|first=Jamal|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> But, new head coach, [[Jeff Fisher]] instilled hope that Bradford was still the Rams franchise quarterback, solidifying this hope when the Rams later reached a deal with the [[Washington Redskins]] for the 2nd overall selection in the [[2012 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/7668243/washington-redskins-acquire-no-2-overall-pick-st-louis-rams |title=Redskins acquire No. 2 pick from Rams |last=Schefter |first=Adam |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sbradford.jpg|thumb|left|280px|upright=3.|Bradford throwing against the New York Jets in 2012]]\nThe Rams weren't expected to make much of a leap following their dismal campaign the year before, but behind strong play by Bradford and rookies stepping up to the challenge, the Rams finished 7-8-1.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/ |title=2012 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> In Week 2, against the Washington Redskins, he finished with 310 passing yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the 31\u201328 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209160ram.htm |title=Washington Redskins at St. Louis Rams - September 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> In Week 15, against the Minnesota Vikings, he had 377 passing yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the 36\u201322 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212160ram.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at St. Louis Rams - December 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> Bradford finished the season with career best numbers: 3,702 passing yards, 21 touchdowns compared to 13 interceptions and an 82.6 passer rating to go along with 59.5 completion percentage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BradSa00/gamelog/2012 |title=Sam Bradford 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\nWith all the additions in the off-season, the Rams and Bradford were expected to excel in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.turfshowtimes.com/2013/9/4/4694944/2013-nfl-season-predictions-st-louis-rams-super-bowl|title=Rams to the Super Bowl!|last=Bibber|first=Ryan Van|date=2013-09-04|website=Turf Show Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> The season started off on a positive note with a 27\u201324 victory over the Arizona Cardinals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080ram.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at St. Louis Rams - September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> In the game, Bradford had 299 passing yards, two touchdowns, and an interception. In the next game against the Atlanta Falcons, he had 352 passing yards, three touchdowns, and one interception as the Rams fell 31\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309150atl.htm |title=St. Louis Rams at Atlanta Falcons - September 15th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> After two losses to the Dallas Cowboys and San Francisco 49ers, he had 222 passing yards and three touchdowns in a 34\u201320 victory over the Jacksonville Jaguars.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310060ram.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at St. Louis Rams - October 6th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> For the second straight game, he threw for three touchdowns in a 38\u201313 victory over the Houston Texans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310130htx.htm |title=St. Louis Rams at Houston Texans - October 13th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> However, during the Rams Week 7 game against the [[Carolina Panthers]], Bradford tore his left ACL on a run out of bounds after a hit from safety [[Mike Mitchell (safety)|Mike Mitchell]], ending his season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/9855679/sam-bradford-st-louis-rams-suffers-torn-acl-source-says |title=Source: Rams QB Bradford suffers torn ACL |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On the 2013 season, Bradford passed for 1,687 yards and 14 touchdowns to 4 interceptions and 90.9 passer rating.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BradSa00/gamelog/2013 |title=Sam Bradford 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> The Rams missed the playoffs with a 7\u20139 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/ram/2013.htm |title=2013 St. Louis Rams Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season: Lost season====\n[[File:Sam Bradford 2014.jpg|thumb|180px|Bradford in 2014]]\nBradford suffered an injury to the same ACL after being sacked during a preseason game against the [[Cleveland Browns]] and missed the entire 2014 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000382460/article/sam-bradford-out-for-season-with-torn-acl |title=Sam Bradford out for season with torn ACL |last=Sessler |first=Marc |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Philadelphia Eagles===\n[[File:Sam Bradford 2015.jpg|200px|thumb|Bradford with the Philadelphia Eagles in 2015]]\n\nOn March 10, 2015, Bradford was traded to the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] along with a 2015 fifth round pick, in exchange for [[Nick Foles]], a 2015 fourth-round pick, and a 2016 second-round pick.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Rams trading Sam Bradford to Eagles for Nick Foles|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000477790/article/rams-trading-sam-bradford-to-eagles-for-nick-foles|publisher=NFL.com|accessdate=March 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Florio|first1=Mike|title=Eagles give up 2016 second-rounder for Bradford, too|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/03/10/eagles-give-up-2016-second-rounder-for-bradford-too/|publisher=Pro Football Talk|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sheridan|first1=Phil|title=QBs Bradford, Foles swap teams|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/12456228/sam-bradford-st-louis-rams-traded-philadelphia-eagles-nick-foles|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref> In his first game as a Philadelphia Eagle, Bradford completed 36 out of 52 passes for a touchdown and two interceptions in a season opening 26\u201324 loss to the [[Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Watch Philadelphia Eagles vs. Atlanta Falcons [09/14/2015] - NFL.com|url = http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2015091400/2015/REG1/eagles@falcons#menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%253A0ap3000000530981&tab=analyze|website = www.nfl.com|accessdate = September 20, 2015}}</ref> In Week 4, he threw three touchdowns with zero interceptions, and although his completion percentage was lower than 55% in both games, he still mustered a 122.6 passer rating in a loss to the Redskins, his only passer rating above 90 for the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510040was.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at Washington Redskins - October 4th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In Week 6, he threw three interceptions, but the Eagles still gained a 27\u20137 win over the New York Giants to move Philadelphia to 3\u20133 and in first place in the NFC East, mainly thanks to the defense and run game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/new-york-giants-philadelphia-eagles-20151019021/|title=NY Giants 7 - 27 Philadelphia: Final - 2015-10-19 - National Football League - Yahoo! Sports|website=Yahoo Sports|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Bradford had his worst game by far in a loss against the Panthers, where he completed only 56.5% of his passes with zero touchdowns, one interception, and a quarterback rating of 58.7.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510250car.htm |title= Philadelphia Eagles at Carolina Panthers - October 25th, 2015 |website= Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date= November 9, 2017}}</ref> Against the [[Miami Dolphins]] on November 15, Bradford suffered a left shoulder injury as well as a concussion, which would keep him out of the next two games against [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay]] and a Thanksgiving Day game against [[2015 Detroit Lions season|Detroit]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14137917/sam-bradford-philadelphia-eagles-injures-shoulder-ruled-vs-miami-dolphins-x-rays-negative |title= Sam Bradford injures shoulder, gets concussion; X-rays negative|first=Phil |last=Sheridan |date=November 15, 2015 |work=ESPN.com}}</ref> In his first season, Bradford would go 7-7 as a starter and his play began to improve after Week 9 against the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BradSa00/gamelog/2015/ |title=Sam Bradford 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Before week 9, Bradford has been playing poorly through his first seven games, but Eagles coach [[Chip Kelly]] would not bench him, but during Week 9, Bradford threw a game-winning touchdown in overtime to [[Jordan Matthews]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511080dal.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at Dallas Cowboys - November 8th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In Week 13, Bradford led the Eagles to a 35\u201328 upset over the [[New England Patriots]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512060nwe.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at New England Patriots - December 6th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, Bradford threw for 361 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in a 40\u201317 loss to the Arizona Cardinals.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200phi.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at Philadelphia Eagles - December 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> In Week 16, he threw for 380 yards and a touchdown in a 38\u201324 loss to the Washington Redskins.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512260phi.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Philadelphia Eagles - December 26th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> In the regular season finale against the New York Giants, he threw for 320 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the 35\u201330 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601030nyg.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at New York Giants - January 3rd, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> The Eagles finished with a 7\u20139 record and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/phi/2015.htm |title=2015 Philadelphia Eagles Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2016, Bradford signed a 2-year, $36 million ($26 million guaranteed) contract extension with the Eagles. However, the Eagles traded with the [[Cleveland Browns]] for the number two pick in the [[2016 NFL draft]], in order to draft a new quarterback. This led to speculation that Bradford would be traded or used as a stopgap while [[Chase Daniel]] educates the newly drafted quarterback in Pederson's offensive scheme. On April 25, 2016, it was reported that Bradford wanted to be traded and that he would no longer attend the team's off-season activities.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/15353852/sam-bradford-demanding-trade-philadelphia-eagles | title=Sam Bradford demands trade after Eagles' move for No. 2 pick | publisher=espn.go.com | date=April 25, 2016 | accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> The Eagles selected quarterback [[Carson Wentz]] with the second overall pick in the 2016 draft on April 28. Bradford returned to the team in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000660779/article/sam-bradford-reports-for-eagles-voluntary-workouts | title=Sam Bradford reports for Eagles voluntary workouts | publisher=nfl.com | date=May 9, 2016 | accessdate=September 3, 2016 | author=Patra, Kevin}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\n[[File:Sam Bradford behind center 2016 vs. Redskins.jpg|thumb|180px|Bradford (No. 8) with the Vikings in 2016]]\n\n====2016 season====\nOn September 3, 2016, following his appearance in the Eagles' preseason games, Bradford was traded to the [[Minnesota Vikings]] for a first-round pick in the [[2017 NFL Draft]] (later used to select [[Derek Barnett]]) and a conditional fourth-round pick in the [[2018 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000694979/article/sam-bradford-traded-to-vikings-for-two-draft-picks|title=Sam Bradford traded to Vikings for two draft picks|last=Orr|first=Conor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philadelphiaeagles.com/news/article-1/Sam-Bradford-Traded-To-Minnesota/390017a6-3441-4a43-b39b-eeb1a65dbe64|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170521010249/https://www.philadelphiaeagles.com/news/article-1/Sam-Bradford-Traded-To-Minnesota/390017a6-3441-4a43-b39b-eeb1a65dbe64|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 21, 2017|title=Sam Bradford Traded To Minnesota|last=Smith|first=Alex}}</ref> The trade was made after Vikings quarterback [[Teddy Bridgewater]] suffered a season-ending ACL tear during team practice on August 30, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17424174/teddy-bridgewater-suffers-serious-knee-injury-minnesota-vikings-practice |title=Vikings QB Teddy Bridgewater dislocates knee, tears ACL in drill |last=Goessling |first=Ben  |date=August 30, 2016 |access-date=August 30, 2016 |publisher=espn.com}}</ref>\n\n15 days after being traded, Bradford made his first start for the Vikings in Week 2 against the [[Green Bay Packers]]. Despite not having much time to learn the offense, Bradford outplayed [[Aaron Rodgers]] but ended up hurting his left hand in the first half due to a hit by [[Clay Matthews III|Clay Matthews]]. Bradford finished the game completing 22-of-31 passes for 286 yards and two touchdowns, helping lead the Vikings to their first win in their [[U.S. Bank Stadium|new stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609180min.htm |title=Green Bay Packers at Minnesota Vikings - September 18th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> His first touchdown as a Viking came in the second quarter on an eight-yard pass to tight end [[Kyle Rudolph]] in the back of the end zone, while the second touchdown of the night was a 25-yarder to [[Stefon Diggs]] late in the third quarter that gave the Vikings a 17-7 lead. The connection between both players resulted in 182 yards on 9 catches for Diggs, a career-high for him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/dominant-sam-bradford-outplays-aaron-rodgers-in-vikings-debut-8-takeaways/ |title=Dominant Sam Bradford outplays Aaron Rodgers in Vikings debut: 8 takeaways |last=Wilson |first=Ryan |website=cbssports.com |access-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Bradford received high praise from the media, with many calling it one of the best games of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vikings.com/news/lunch-break/article-1/Peter-King-on-Sam-Bradfords-Performance-vs-Packers-Best-Night-as-a-Pro/c3f2e11a-e90d-489c-949f-77dada5f9f3e|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005804/https://www.vikings.com/news/lunch-break/article-1/Peter-King-on-Sam-Bradfords-Performance-vs-Packers-Best-Night-as-a-Pro/c3f2e11a-e90d-489c-949f-77dada5f9f3e|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 10, 2017|title=Peter King on Sam Bradford's Performance vs. Packers: 'Best Night as a Pro'|website=vikings.com|access-date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> The following week, Bradford threw for 171 yards and one touchdown in a 22-10 win against the [[Carolina Panthers]], thanks to a strong Vikings' defense that sacked [[Cam Newton]] eight times and intercepted him three times.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609250car.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Carolina Panthers - September 25th, 2016 |website= Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date= November 9, 2017}}</ref> In the Vikings' win over the [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] in Week 4, Bradford threw a touchdown pass and did not throw an interception for the third straight game. The only other Vikings player to do that in each of his first three games of a season was [[Randall Cunningham]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.espn.com/espn/elias?date=20161004 |title=Elias Says |website= ESPN.com |accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> With both starting tackles and Stefon Diggs (Vikings' leading receiver) out for a Week 5 game against the [[Houston Texans]], Bradford delivered another strong performance, completing 22 of 30 passes for 271 yards, two touchdowns and, for the fourth straight start, not a single interception. In the opening drive, he connected with [[Adam Thielen]] on a 36-yard touchdown strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/sam-bradford-stands-out-for-vikings-despite-loss-of-another-starting-lineman/396471861/|title=Sam Bradford stands out for Vikings despite loss of another starting lineman|website=startribune.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> During a game against the Detroit Lions, Bradford threw a pass which was batted into the air by Lions defensive tackle [[Tyrunn Walker]]. After which, Bradford caught the ball and ran towards the sideline, gaining five yards in the process.\n\nDuring a three-game losing streak, Bradford threw only three touchdowns and an interception with 725 yards and a 66% completion percentage, poor in comparison with the previous four games, in which he threw for 990 yards, six touchdowns, no interceptions, and had a 70% completion percentage. The Vikings would finish the season with an 8-8 record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/13197/sam-bradford|title=Sam Bradford|website=ESPN.com|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/min/2016.htm |title=2016 Minnesota Vikings Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBradford started 15 games in 2016, completing 395 of 552 passes for 3,877 yards and 20 touchdowns with 5 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/player/sambradford/497095/profile | title=Sam Bradford | publisher=nfl.com | accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> His 71.6 completion percentage set a single season NFL record, passing [[Drew Brees]]'s 2011 mark of 71.2.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/sam-bradford-sam-bradford-accurate-qb-nfl-history-010117 |title=Sam Bradford \u2014 Sam Bradford! \u2014 is the most accurate QB in NFL history |last=Graf |first=Dan |date=January 1, 2017 |publisher=foxsports.com |access-date=January 1, 2017}}</ref> Brees later finished the 2017 season with a 72.0 completion percentage, retaking the record. Bradford's 395 completions set a franchise record for completions in a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Sam-Bradford-Breaks-NFL-Record-Team-Records-in-Season-Finale/bf5f32ae-be3a-4005-8c55-8f64f8480c94 |title=Sam Bradford Breaks NFL Record, Team Records in Season Finale |last=Young |first=Lindsey |date=January 1, 2017 |publisher=vikings.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103162516/https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Sam-Bradford-Breaks-NFL-Record-Team-Records-in-Season-Finale/bf5f32ae-be3a-4005-8c55-8f64f8480c94 |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |url-status=dead |access-date=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nIn Week 1, on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Bradford completed 27-of-32 pass attempts for 346 yards and 3 touchdowns in a 29\u201319 win over the [[2017 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], earning him his first NFC Offensive Player of the Week award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000844276/article/alex-smith-sam-bradford-among-players-of-the-week |title=Alex Smith, Sam Bradford among Players of the Week |last=Lam |first=Quang M. |date=September 13, 2017 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He was inactive for the Week 2 game against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] due to a knee injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000845963/article/sam-bradford-wont-play-sunday-due-to-sore-knee |title=Sam Bradford won't play Sunday due to sore knee |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=September 17, 2017 |publisher=nfl.com |access-date=September 17, 2017}}</ref> After missing three more games, on October 10, it was revealed that Bradford was diagnosed with wear and tear on his knee after two previous ACL surgeries.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shook|first1=Nick|title=Sam Bradford dealing with wear and tear to knee|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000859835/article/sam-bradford-dealing-with-wear-and-tear-to-knee|publisher=NFL|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref> On November 7, Bradford underwent a knee scope, putting his season in jeopardy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shook|first1=Nick|title=Sam Bradford undergoes knee scope, could land on IR|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000874009/article/sam-bradford-undergoes-knee-scope-could-land-on-ir|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref> He was placed on injured reserve the next day, ending his season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Vikings-Activate-Teddy-Bridgewater-Place-Sam-Bradford-on-Injured-Reserve/7204244f-a32d-475c-ab84-20e9241c2d2d |title=Vikings Activate Teddy Bridgewater, Place Sam Bradford on Injured Reserve |last=Peters |first=Craig |date=November 8, 2017 |website=Vikings.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213030903/https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Vikings-Activate-Teddy-Bridgewater-Place-Sam-Bradford-on-Injured-Reserve/7204244f-a32d-475c-ab84-20e9241c2d2d |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On January 13, 2018, Bradford was activated off injured reserve to the active roster for the divisional round of the playoffs against the New Orleans Saints, however [[Case Keenum]] started the game due to his strong season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Vikings-Activate-Sam-Bradford/9b8f5965-2a58-4899-add6-42f8f6f04d37 |title=Vikings Activate Sam Bradford |last=Peters |first=Craig |date=January 13, 2018 |website=Vikings.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202223100/https://www.vikings.com/news/article-1/Vikings-Activate-Sam-Bradford/9b8f5965-2a58-4899-add6-42f8f6f04d37 |archive-date=February 2, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\n====2018 season====\nOn March 16, 2018, Bradford signed a two-year contract with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] worth up to $20 million the first year with $15 million guaranteed with a potential out after 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Urban|first1=Darren|title=Sam Bradford Officially Joins Cardinals|url=https://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Sam-Bradford-Officially-Joins-Cardinals/1ec5358c-ef06-4232-ac1f-70eed65d3ff1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180317092351/https://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Sam-Bradford-Officially-Joins-Cardinals/1ec5358c-ef06-4232-ac1f-70eed65d3ff1|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 17, 2018|website=AZCardinals.com|date=March 16, 2018}}</ref> Bradford wore number 9 with the Cardinals, due to number 8 having been retired in honor of [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] safety [[Larry Wilson (American football)|Larry Wilson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/arizona-cardinals/post/_/id/29767 |title=Sam Bradford to wear No. 9 as Cardinals newcomers get numbers |last=Weinfuss |first=Josh |date=2018-03-30 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref> After ineffective performances in the first two games, both blowout losses, Bradford was pulled in favor of rookie [[Josh Rosen]] in the final moments of a Week 3 loss to the [[2018 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000965850/article/josh-rosen-replaces-sam-bradford-late-in-cards-loss|title=Josh Rosen replaces Sam Bradford late in Cards loss|website=NFL.com|date=September 23, 2018|first = Kevin|last = Patra}}</ref> As the Cardinals decided to keep Rosen as their starting quarterback, Bradford was inactive for the next five weeks before ultimately being released on November 3, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shook |first1=Nick |title=Cardinals release Sam Bradford after eight weeks |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000983649/article/cardinals-release-sam-bradford-after-eight-weeks |website=NFL.com |accessdate=November 3, 2018}}</ref> Bradford's deal with the Cardinals is considered one of the worst free agent signings of the 2010s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arizonasports.com/story/2287762/b-r-sam-bradfords-deal-cardinals-ranks-among-last-decades-worst/|title=B/R: Sam Bradford's deal with Cardinals ranks among last decade's worst|date=2020-03-09|website=Arizona Sports|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|<center>Legend</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n|Led the league\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"8\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Sacked\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Sck !! YdsL !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2010 NFL season|2010]] !! [[2010 St. Louis Rams season|STL]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 354 || '''590''' || 60.0 || 3,512 || 6.0 || 18|| '''15''' || 76.5 || 27|| 63 || 2.3 || '''1''' || 34 || 244 || 7 || 2\n|-\n! [[2011 NFL season|2011]] !! [[2011 St. Louis Rams season|STL]]\n| 10 || 10 || 191 || 357 || 53.5 || 2,164 || 6.1 || 6 || 6 || 70.5 || 18 || 26 || 1.4 || 0 || 36 || 248 || '''10''' || '''7'''\n|-\n! [[2012 NFL season|2012]] !! [[2012 St. Louis Rams season|STL]]\n|| '''16''' || '''16''' || 328 || 551 || 59.5 || 3,702 || 6.7 || '''21''' || 13 || 82.6 || '''36''' || '''124''' || 3.4 || '''1''' || 35 || 233 || 7 || 1\n|- 65.4 9. 97.4 2.4\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 St. Louis Rams season|STL]]\n| 7 || 7 || 159 || 262 || 60.7 || 1,687 || 6.4 || 14|| 4 || 90.9 || 15 || 31 || 2.1 || 0 || 15 || 97 || 3 || 1\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 St. Louis Rams season|STL]]\n| 0 || 0 || colspan=\"16\"| '''''did not play due to injury'''''\n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] !! [[2015 Philadelphia Eagles season|PHI]]