eracing.com/}}\n* {{Racing-Reference driver|Dominique_Van_Wieringen}}\n\n{{Rette Jones Racing}}\n{{Youngs Motorsports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Wieringen, Dominique}}\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:NASCAR drivers]]\n[[Category:American female racing drivers]]\n[[Category:People from Amherstburg, Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Luks25", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:she is Canadian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominique_Van_Wieringen"}
{"title_page": "Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham", "text_new": "'''[[:he:\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea_\u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8_\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|Yeshiva Yerucham]]'''\n\n'''Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd}}) is a [[Hesder|hesder yeshiva]] located in the development town of [[Yeruham]], [[Israel]]. It was founded in 1993 and currently there are over 220 students<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />. It is known for its high level of learning and for being one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in Israel. [[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham.jpg|thumbnail|A picture of the outside of Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham. ]]\n==History==\n[[File:Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva.png|thumb|Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva]]In the early 1970s, a group of [[Religious Zionism|Religious Zionists]] settled in Yeruham with the goal of imporving the south of Israel, and helping to increase the quality of life for the residents of Yerucham.  Over time, the group grew in number and expanded its activities by taking on educational responsibilities as well. After establishing \"Midreshet B'Yahad\", a Seminar Center of Judaism, Society and Zionism Studies, the group realized the need for a [[yeshiva]] as the next step in strengthening the existing projects by bringing youth to Yeruham.\n\nThe leader of this group, Shmuel Friedman Ben-Shalom, approached [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Eliyhau Blumenzweig]], who at the time taught at [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], with a proposition to be the Rosh Yeshiva, which he accepted. The yeshiva subsequently opened its doors in 1993<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%91%D7%A8%D7%A0%D7%96%D7%94/943418-%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%91%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%94%D7%A1%D7%93%D7%A8-%D7%91%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%97%D7%9D-%D7%97%D7%92%D7%92%D7%94-%D7%97%D7%A6%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%95%D7%91%D7%9C/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d2\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d7\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05d1\u05dc|date=2019-07-08|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%99%D7%94%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA/%d7%99%d7%a9%d7%99%d7%91%d7%aa-%d7%99%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%97%d7%9d-%d7%97%d7%95%d7%92%d7%92%d7%aa-20-%d7%a9%d7%a0%d7%95%d7%aa-%d7%aa%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%94/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d5\u05d2\u05d2\u05ea 20 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4|date=2012-08-29|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/index.php?lang=he|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.  \n\nToday, the yeshiva is considered to be one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in the country.\n\n==Curriculum==\n[[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yeruham Old Building.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]\nYeshivat HaHesder Yerucham emphasizes the importance of learning [[Talmud]] in depth, specifically through applying the [[Brisker method|Brisker Method]]. A typical day in Yeshiva will include two sessions of intensive Talmud study (''iyun'') and one of extensive study (''bekiut''). \n\nShachris at the Yeshiva is at 6:30am, followed by halachah seder until 8:00am. Breakfast is from 8:00am-8:30am. After breakfast is morning seder, which is typically gemara iyun, and it goes from 8:30am-1:00pm. Following morning seder is lunch and a break from 1:00pm-3pm. Mincha is at 3:00pm, followed by afternoon seder, from about 3:20pm-7:30pm. Afternoon seder consists of more iyun gemara, followed by a couple hours of emmunah. Many of the students use the entire afternoon seder for learning machshava, tanach, mussar, and emmunah. From 7:30pm-8:00pm is Maariv, followed by supper from 8:00pm-8:30pm. Night seder consists of learning bekiut, and it goes from 8:30pm until at least 11:00pm, although there is no given time for night seder to end, and many students learn until much later.[[File:Hayeshiva.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]'''Daily Schedule''': \n\nShachrit: 6:30am-8:00am\n\nBreakfast: 8:00am-8:30am\n\nMorning seder: 8:30am-1:00pm\n\nLunch/break: 1:00pm-3:00pm\n\nMincha: 3:00pm-3:20pm\n\nAfternoon seder: 3:20pm-7:30pm\n\nSupper: 7:30pm-8:00pm\n\nMarriv: 8:00pm-8:30pm \n\nNight seder: 8:30pm-11:00pm (or later)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/26/46/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.yhy.co.il|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\nThe yeshiva guides its students to base their perspective upon the teachings of [[Yehuda Halevi|Rabbi Yehuda Halevi]] and the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]] in accordance with the ideology of [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], as is often customary in Religious Zionist yeshivas. With the goal of educating students to deal independently with the challenges they face living as an observant Jews in modern time in mind, the yeshiva encourages a broader study of Biblical, rabbinic, and other classical and modern sources. Hence, the yeshiva curriculum contains weekly classes in [[Tanakh]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Hasidic philosophy]], and the works of Jewish scholars such as [[Maimonides]], [[Nachmanides]], [[Moshe Chaim Luzzatto]], [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]], [[Abraham Isaac Kook]] and many more.\n\n==Educational approach==\nThe yeshiva educates its students to be aware of their surroundings and attentive to the needs of society in general. The yeshiva believes that the keys to solving Israel\u2019s socioeconomic gaps lie in integration and education. All the students volunteer in the community mainly in the field of education. Many of the yeshiva's alumni settle in Yeruham instead of heading to the country's central cities.\n\nThe yeshiva also promotes other programs, among them:\n* ''Ye'adim'' (goals) - Concern of the Ethiopian Jewry in Israel's situation led Yerucham students to create a leadership training program for Ethiopian students with the intention of their returning to their communities. During the 5 years of Hesder the students synchronize their full Yeshiva studies with a [[Bachelor of Education|B.Ed.]] degree in [[Herzog College]].\n* Young Study Partners - First and second year students dedicate 2 hours weekly to studying Torah subjects with children from the local elementary school. They also serve as positive role models for the local youth and look to form a connection with their families.\n* Charity Fund - The goal of the Fund is to help the needy of Yeruham become self-sufficient and better managers of their money. The Fund uses the cooperation of the local welfare and professional financial advisors to this end.\n* ''B'levav Shalem'' Yeshiva High School \u2013 Because of the lack of high quality religious high schools in the [[Negev]], and as a part of the integration program the Hesder Yeshiva believes in, it was decided by alumni, residents of Yerucham, to open a Yeshiva High School for the local and general population.\n\n==Educational staff==\n[[File:\u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2.JPG|thumb|Rabbi Blumenzweig]]\nIn addition to Rabbi Blumenzweig, rabbis who teach in the Yeshiva include Rabbis [[Uriel Eitam]], Chaim Wolfson, Shai Gnizi, Shmuel Gleizer, Achiya Ben Pazi, Shmuel Ariel and Elyakim Sharir<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>. Rabbis Gnizi, Gleizer and Ben Pazi themselves began as students in the yeshiva. There are also rabbis who come from afar to give weekly classes: Rabbis Joseph Elitzor, Eliyahu Bazak and Avi Luria.\nPreviously there were other teachers who have since left. These include physicist and philosopher [[:he:\u05de\u05d9\u05db\u05d0\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd|Rabbi Dr. Michael Abraham]], Ehud Barzilai, Yair Ya'acobi, Meir Kahana and Rabbi Nir Weinberg (who left to establish and head the Hazor'im Yeshiva High-School in the lower Galilee)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hesder]]\n*[[Yeshiva]]\n*[[Yerucham]] \n*[[Torah]] \n*[[Israel]] \n*[[Gemara]]\n*[[Brisker method]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yhy.co.il Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham] (Hebrew)\n*[http://beyachad.dsites.co.il/HTMLs/Home.aspx Midreshet Beyahad] (Hebrew)\n\n==Yeshiva's publications==\n* ''Kutanot Or'' (Coats of Light) - \"A Jewish Perspective on the meaning of [[modesty]] and its value\", collection of essays edited by Yeshiva's students.\n* ''Mimidbar Matana'' (A Present From The Desert) - A monthly newsletter which is sent out to students in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] and alumni.\n* ''Meisharim'' (Righteous) - A journal of articles on a variety of Torah topics, written by the students and teachers, published annually by the Yeshiva.\n* ''Hahazit ShebaOref'' (The Home-Front Front) - A collection of essays dealing with the trials and challenges of a non-combat soldier. The book\u2019s intention is to answer some of the questions that soldiers serving in non-field units, such as the importance of their service, and [[Halakha|halakhic]] perspective on different situations.\n{{Orthodox yeshivot in Israel}}{{Coord|30.9853882|N|34.9274340|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}[[Category:Yeshivot hesder|Yerucham]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Israel]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeshivat_Hesder_Yerucham}}\n", "text_old": "'''[[:he:\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea_\u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8_\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|Yeshiva Yerucham]]'''\n\n'''Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd}}) is a [[Hesder|hesder yeshiva]] located in the development town of [[Yeruham]], [[Israel]]. It was founded in 1993 and currently there are over 220 students<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />. It is known for its high level of learning and for being one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in Israel. [[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham.jpg|thumbnail|A picture of the outside of Yeshivat Hesder Yerucham. ]]\n==History==\n[[File:Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva.png|thumb|Inside the beis medresh of the yeshiva]]In the early 1970s, a group of [[Religious Zionism|Religious Zionists]] settled in Yeruham with the goal of imporving the south of Israel, and helping to increase the quality of life for the residents of Yerucham.  Over time, the group grew in number and expanded its activities by taking on educational responsibilities as well. After establishing \"Midreshet B'Yahad\", a Seminar Center of Judaism, Society and Zionism Studies, the group realized the need for a [[yeshiva]] as the next step in strengthening the existing projects by bringing youth to Yeruham.\n\nThe leader of this group, Shmuel Friedman Ben-Shalom, approached [[:he:\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5_\u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2|Rabbi Eliyhau Blumenzweig]], who at the time taught at [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], with a proposition to be the Rosh Yeshiva, which he accepted. The yeshiva subsequently opened its doors in 1993<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%91%D7%A8%D7%A0%D7%96%D7%94/943418-%D7%99%D7%A9%D7%99%D7%91%D7%AA-%D7%94%D7%94%D7%A1%D7%93%D7%A8-%D7%91%D7%99%D7%A8%D7%95%D7%97%D7%9D-%D7%97%D7%92%D7%92%D7%94-%D7%97%D7%A6%D7%99-%D7%99%D7%95%D7%91%D7%9C/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d1\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d2\u05d2\u05d4 \u05d7\u05e6\u05d9 \u05d9\u05d5\u05d1\u05dc|date=2019-07-08|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kipa.co.il/%D7%99%D7%94%D7%93%D7%95%D7%AA/%d7%99%d7%a9%d7%99%d7%91%d7%aa-%d7%99%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%97%d7%9d-%d7%97%d7%95%d7%92%d7%92%d7%aa-20-%d7%a9%d7%a0%d7%95%d7%aa-%d7%aa%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%94/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd \u05d7\u05d5\u05d2\u05d2\u05ea 20 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05ea\u05d5\u05e8\u05d4|date=2012-08-29|website=\u05db\u05d9\u05e4\u05d4|language=he|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/index.php?lang=he|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.  \n\nToday, the yeshiva is considered to be one of the most serious hesder yeshivas in the country.\n\n==Curriculum==\n[[File:Yeshivat HaHesder Yeruham Old Building.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]\nYeshivat HaHesder Yerucham emphasizes the importance of learning [[Talmud]] in depth, specifically through applying the [[Brisker method|Brisker Method]]. A typical day in Yeshiva will include two sessions of intensive Talmud study (''iyun'') and one of extensive study (''bekiut''). \n\nShachris at the Yeshiva is at 6:30am, followed by halachah seder until 8:00am. Breakfast is from 8:00am-8:30am. After breakfast is morning seder, which is typically gemara iyun, and it goes from 8:30am-1:00pm. Following morning seder is lunch and a break from 1:00pm-3pm. Mincha is at 3:00pm, followed by afternoon seder, from about 3:20pm-7:30pm. Afternoon seder consists of more iyun gemara, followed by a couple hours of emmunah. Many of the students use the entire afternoon seder for learning machshava, tanach, mussar, and emmunah. From 7:30pm-8:00pm is Maariv, followed by supper from 8:00pm-8:30pm. Night seder consists of learning bekiut, and it goes from 8:30pm until at least 11:00pm, although there is no given time for night seder to end, and many students learn until much later.[[File:Hayeshiva.jpg|thumb|Lunch room of the Yeshiva]]'''Daily Schedule''': \n\nShachrit: 6:30am-8:00am\n\nBreakfast: 8:00am-8:30am\n\nMorning seder: 8:30am-1:00pm\n\nLunch/break: 1:00pm-3:00pm\n\nMincha: 3:00pm-3:20pm\n\nAfternoon seder: 3:20pm-7:30pm\n\nSupper: 7:30pm-8:00pm\n\nMarriv: 8:00pm-8:30pm \n\nNight seder: 8:30pm-11:00pm (or later)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/26/46/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.yhy.co.il|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n\nThe yeshiva guides its students to base their perspective upon the teachings of [[Yehuda Halevi|Rabbi Yehuda Halevi]] and the [[Judah Loew ben Bezalel|Maharal of Prague]] in accordance with the ideology of [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], as is often customary in Religious Zionist yeshivas.\nWith the goal of educating students to deal independently with the challenges they face living as an observant Jews in modern time in mind, the yeshiva encourages a broader study of Biblical, rabbinic, and other classical and modern sources. Hence, the yeshiva curriculum contains weekly classes in [[Tanakh]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Hasidic philosophy]], and the works of Jewish  scholars such as [[Moshe Chaim Luzzatto]], [[Maimonides]], [[Judah Halevi]], [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]] and [[Abraham Isaac Kook]].\n\n==Educational approach==\nThe yeshiva educates its students to be aware of their surroundings and attentive to the needs of society in general. The yeshiva believes that the keys to solving Israel\u2019s socioeconomic gaps lie in integration and education. All the students volunteer in the community mainly in the field of education. Many of the yeshiva's alumni settle in Yeruham instead of heading to the country's central cities.\n\nThe yeshiva also promotes other programs, among them:\n* ''Ye'adim'' (goals) - Concern of the Ethiopian Jewry in Israel's situation led Yerucham students to create a leadership training program for Ethiopian students with the intention of their returning to their communities. During the 5 years of Hesder the students synchronize their full Yeshiva studies with a [[Bachelor of Education|B.Ed.]] degree in [[Herzog College]].\n* Young Study Partners - First and second year students dedicate 2 hours weekly to studying Torah subjects with children from the local elementary school. They also serve as positive role models for the local youth and look to form a connection with their families.\n* Charity Fund - The goal of the Fund is to help the needy of Yeruham become self-sufficient and better managers of their money. The Fund uses the cooperation of the local welfare and professional financial advisors to this end.\n* ''B'levav Shalem'' Yeshiva High School \u2013 Because of the lack of high quality religious high schools in the [[Negev]], and as a part of the integration program the Hesder Yeshiva believes in, it was decided by alumni, residents of Yerucham, to open a Yeshiva High School for the local and general population.\n\n==Educational staff==\n[[File:\u05d4\u05e8\u05d1 \u05d1\u05dc\u05d5\u05de\u05e0\u05e6\u05d5\u05d9\u05d2.JPG|thumb|Rabbi Blumenzweig]]\nIn addition to Rabbi Blumenzweig, rabbis who teach in the Yeshiva include Rabbis [[Uriel Eitam]], Chaim Wolfson, Shai Gnizi, Shmuel Gleizer, Achiya Ben Pazi, Shmuel Ariel and Elyakim Sharir<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>. Rabbis Gnizi, Gleizer and Ben Pazi themselves began as students in the yeshiva. There are also rabbis who come from afar to give weekly classes: Rabbis Joseph Elitzor, Eliyahu Bazak and Avi Luria.\nPreviously there were other teachers who have since left. These include physicist and philosopher [[:he:\u05de\u05d9\u05db\u05d0\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05e8\u05d4\u05dd|Rabbi Dr. Michael Abraham]], Ehud Barzilai, Yair Ya'acobi, Meir Kahana and Rabbi Nir Weinberg (who left to establish and head the Hazor'im Yeshiva High-School in the lower Galilee)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhy.co.il/content/blogcategory/33/51/lang,he/|title=\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05ea \u05d4\u05d4\u05e1\u05d3\u05e8 \u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05d7\u05dd - \u05e6\u05d5\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05d1\u05d4|website=www.yhy.co.il|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hesder]]\n*[[Yeshiva]]\n*[[Yerucham]] \n*[[Torah]] \n*[[Israel]] \n*[[Gemara]]\n*[[Brisker method]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.yhy.co.il Yeshivat HaHesder Yerucham] (Hebrew)\n*[http://beyachad.dsites.co.il/HTMLs/Home.aspx Midreshet Beyahad] (Hebrew)\n\n==Yeshiva's publications==\n* ''Kutanot Or'' (Coats of Light) - \"A Jewish Perspective on the meaning of [[modesty]] and its value\", collection of essays edited by Yeshiva's students.\n* ''Mimidbar Matana'' (A Present From The Desert) - A monthly newsletter which is sent out to students in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] and alumni.\n* ''Meisharim'' (Righteous) - A journal of articles on a variety of Torah topics, written by the students and teachers, published annually by the Yeshiva.\n* ''Hahazit ShebaOref'' (The Home-Front Front) - A collection of essays dealing with the trials and challenges of a non-combat soldier. The book\u2019s intention is to answer some of the questions that soldiers serving in non-field units, such as the importance of their service, and [[Halakha|halakhic]] perspective on different situations.\n{{Orthodox yeshivot in Israel}}{{Coord|30.9853882|N|34.9274340|E|source:hewiki_region:IL_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title}}[[Category:Yeshivot hesder|Yerucham]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Israel]]\n\n== Bibliography ==\n<references responsive=\"0\" />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeshivat_Hesder_Yerucham}}\n", "name_user": "Avishai Lightstone", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yeshivat_HaHesder_Yerucham"}
{"title_page": "USS Tucker (DD-374)", "text_new": "{{other ships|USS Tucker}}\n{{short description|Mahan-class destroyer}}\n{{coord missing|Pacific Ocean}}\n{{good article}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Tucker DD-374.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Tucker'' off the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]], [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], 2{{nbsp}}March 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1942}}\n|Ship name=''Tucker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Samuel Tucker]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Norfolk Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=15 August 1934\n|Ship launched=26 February 1936\n|Ship commissioned=23 July 1936\n|Ship struck=2 December 1944\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Struck [[Naval mine|mine]] off [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]], 4{{nbsp}}August 1942\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=(as built)\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|1500|LT|t|0|lk=in}} ([[standard load]])\n*{{convert|1725|LT|t}} ([[deep load]])\n|Ship length={{convert|341|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship power=*{{convert|46,000|shp|lk=on}}\n*4 [[water-tube boiler]]s           \n|Ship propulsion=2 [[Propeller shaft|shafts]] 2 geared [[steam turbine]]s\n|Ship speed={{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship complement=158 officers and enlisted men\n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[gun director]] above bridge\n|Ship armament=*5 \u00d7 single [[5\"/38 caliber gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}]] [[DP gun]]s\n*3 \u00d7 quadruple [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 in (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*4 \u00d7 single [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] AA machine guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] stern racks\n*Depth charge projectors (aka [[K-guns]])\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Tucker'' (DD-374)''' was a {{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]] and was commissioned in 1936. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]].\n\nFirst assigned to the [[United States Battle Fleet]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]], ''Tucker'' operated along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] and in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. After participating in [[naval exercise]]s in the [[Caribbean Sea]], she returned to duty in [[Territory of Hawaii|Hawaii]]. She then went on a goodwill tour to New Zealand, returning to Hawaii and docking at [[Pearl Harbor]]. When the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7{{nbsp}}December 1941, ''Tucker'' was undergoing an overhaul and was not attacked. Soon afterward, she began escorting convoys between the West Coast and Hawaii. ''Tucker'' was then tasked with escort duty to islands in the [[South Pacific Ocean|Sourth Pacific]].\n\n''Tucker'' steamed out of port on 1 August 1942, escorting a [[cargo ship]] to [[Espiritu Santo]]. They entered its harbor three days later, where the destroyer unknowingly entered a defensive [[minefield]] laid by the US Navy. ''Tucker'' struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]] that tore her almost in two, sinking her and killing three sailors; the rest of the crew survived.\n\n==Design==\n\n===General characteristics===  \nThe [[Mahan-class destroyer]]s were improved versions of the preceding [[Farragut-class destroyer (1934)|''Farragut'' class]].{{sfn|Reiilly| 1983| p=28}} The ''Mahan''s' [[standard displacement]] was {{convert|150|LT|t|0|lk=in}} larger, and they were equipped with a more efficient steam [[propulsion]] system and designed to carry 12 torpedo tubes, an increase of four over the Farragut-class.  \n{{snf|Friedman| 2004| p=88}} \n\n''Tucker'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|1500|LT|t|0|lk=on}}\nat [[standard load]] and {{convert|1725|LT|t}} at [[deep load]]. The ship's [[length overall|overall length]] was {{convert|341|ft|m|1}}, her [[beam (nautical)|beam]] was {{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|1}}, and her [[draft (hull)|draft]] was {{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|1}}. Her peace-time complement consisted of 158 officers and enlisted men.{{snf|Friedman|2004|pp=465\u2013466}}\n\nShe had a [[Tripod mast|tripod]] [[foremast]] and a pole mainmast. To improve the [[antiaircraft]] [[field of fire (weaponry)|field of fire]], her [[tripod]] foremast was constructed without nautical [[rigging]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}} The destroyer was fitted with emergency [[diesel generators]], replacing the storage batteries of earlier destroyers. Gun crew shelters were also built fore and aft for the superimposed guns. A third set of quadruple torpedo tubes was added, with one mounted on the [[centerline (nautical)|centerline]] and two in the side positions.{{sfn |Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n===Machinery and armament===\n''Tucker'' was fitted with four [[water-tube boiler]]s built by either [[Babcock & Wilcox]] or [[Foster Wheeler]]. They generated the steam that propelled the two [[General Electric]] geared [[steam turbine]]s, developing {{convert|46,000|shp|abbr=on|lk=on}} for a maximum speed of {{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}. ''Tucker'' carried a maximum of {{convert|523|LT|t}} of [[fuel oil]], with a trial range of {{convert|7300|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}. The ship's\nwartime ranges were {{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}} and {{convert|4360|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|20|kn|lk=in}}.\nThe ship's design incorporated a new generation of land-based propulsion machinery. The boilers were capable of reaching {{convert|650\u2013700|F|C|sigfig=2}}, powering the high-pressure turbines with [[double reduction gearing|double reduction gears]] that enabled the turbines to run faster and more efficiently than in previous destroyer designs.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]], equipped with the MK{{nbsp}}33 gun [[fire-control system]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} \nThe ship's antiaircraft battery had four water-cooled [[.50 caliber machine gun]]s (12.7&nbsp;mm).{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=111}} The ship was fitted with three quadruple torpedo-tube mounts for twelve {{convert|21|in|mm|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo]]es, guided by the Mark{{nbsp}}27 torpedo fire-control system. Each of the three mounts held four torpedoes. Those on the [[Port and starboard|port]] and [[Port and starboard|starboard]] sides could only fire [[broadside]], but the centerline mount could fire from either side.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} She was rigged for two [[depth charge]] roll-off racks and for depth charge projectors (K-guns).{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=86}} In early 1942, the Navy began to refit the ''Mahan''-class destroyers with new antiaircraft armament, although most of the class was not refitted until sometime in 1944. (The source, Hodges and Friedman, do not indicate if ''Tucker'' was refitted). {{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=145}}\n\n==Construction and service history==\n\n''Tucker'' was one of eighteen [[Mahan-class destroyer|Mahan-class destroyers]] and was built at the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]].{{sfn|Conway's|1980|pp=125\u2013126}} She was the second vessel to be named for [[Samuel Tucker]], who had been an officer in the [[Continental Navy]] and the United States Navy.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=67}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[keel]] was laid down on 15{{nbsp}}August 1934. She was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 26{{nbsp}}February 1936 and [[Ceremonial ship launching|christened]] by a third cousin of Tucker. The ship was commissioned in the United States Navy on 23{{nbsp}}July, with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] George T. Howard in command.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68-69}}\n\n[[File:USS Tucker.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval warship rigged with sails|''Tucker'' rigged with sails, June 1940]]\nAfter her [[shakedown cruise]], she joined destroyer forces attached to the United States Battle Fleet in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. She operated with them along the West Coast and in the Hawaiian islands as part of Destroyer Squadron{{nbsp}}3 of the Destroyer Division.\nIn February 1939, she took part in [[Fleet Problem&nbsp;XX]], a naval exercise held in the Caribbean Sea and Atlantic Ocean and observed by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. As tensions with Japan increased, the fleet was ordered to return to Hawaiian waters.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nIn June 1940, ''Tucker'' steamed from Hawaii to a location east of [[Wake Island]] for fleet exercises. In ''United States Navy Destroyers of World War II,'' John Reilly, Jr. described the uncommon method used to power the vessel on its return to Hawaii: {{blockquote|... Tucker stretched her fuel supply by rigging Sails. Her homemade [[foresail]] and [[mainsail]] moved Tucker at an estimated 3.4 knots, letting her maintain [[Glossary of nautical terms#steerageway|steerageway]] as she loitered on station several days.{{sfn|Reilly|1983|p=30}}}}\n\n''Tucker'' continued operating between Hawaii and the West Coast into February 1941. She then set course for New Zealand on a goodwill tour, arriving in [[Auckland]] on 17 March. Returning to Pearl Harbor, she took part in routine exercises at sea before returning to her homeport of San Diego on 19{{nbsp}}September. After a short stay, ''Tucker'' steamed to Hawaii in November as part of Task Force{{nbsp}}19, operating again in the Hawaiian Islands. Shortly afterward, she put into Pearl Harbor for an overhaul by a [[destroyer tender]].{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nWhen the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941, ''Tucker'' was one of five destroyers moored at berth X\u20139, East Loch, alongside the destroyer tender {{USS|Whitney|AD-4|2}}.{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|pp=47\u201348}} Even before ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[general quarters]] alarm could be sounded, one of her on-deck sailors began firing a 50-caliber machine gun at the first wave of Japanese aircraft. When the second wave attacked, every ship that could opened fire. ''Tucker''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on at least two aircraft: one crashed in a cane field, another in flames disappeared over a mountaintop. Because ''Tucker'' was at Pearl Harbor for overhaul, much of her machinery had been torn down for repairs; despite the crew's efforts, they were unable to get the ship underway until that evening.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68}}\n\nAfter her overhaul, ''Tucker'' patrolled off Pearl Harbor and spent several months escorting convoys between Hawaii and the West Coast. With new orders, she steamed to the South Pacific for convoy duty. ''Tucker'' then escorted the auxiliary ship {{USS|Wright|AV-1|2}} to [[Tutuila]], [[American Samoa]], as part of the drive to fortify outposts. She then escorted her charge to [[Suva]], [[British Fiji|Fiji]], and proceeded to [[Noumea]], [[New Caledonia]]. Steaming on for Australia, she arrived at [[Sydney]] on 27{{nbsp}}April. After taking on fuel, she visited [[Melbourne]], [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] before steaming back to Sydney. ''Tucker'' and  ''Wright'' returned to Suva, arriving on 3{{nbsp}}June 1942. For the remainder of June and into the first week of July, ''Tucker'' operated out of Suva before relieving the cruiser {{USS|Boise|CL-47|2}} of convoy escort duties on 10{{nbsp}}July. On{{nbsp}}30 July, the ship arrived at Auckland and the following day started back for Suva.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\n==Fate==\n[[Image:DD-374 sunk 5Aug1942 EspirituSanto NAN09-10-86.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval ship struck by a mine and sinking|USS ''Tucker'' (D-374) sinking south of Espiritu Santo,  5 August 1942]]\n\nOn 1{{nbsp}}August 1942 ''Tucker'' left Suva, escorting the cargo ship SS ''Nira Luckenbach'' to [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]].{{sfn|NHHC}} On 4{{nbsp}}August ''Tucker'' led the cargo ship into the harbor at Espiritu Santo, as she headed into the western entrance, she struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]]. The explosion tore her hull nearly in two at the [[Funnel (ship)|No.{{nbsp}}1 stack]], killing all three crew members on watch in the forward [[fire room]]. The rest of the ship's company survived.\n''Nira Luckenbach'' and other vessels rescued sailors from their sinking ship. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[stern]] sank the following morning; a diving party scuttled and sank her [[bow (ship)|bow]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}} The ship had steamed into the [[Segond Channel]] unaware that the minelayers {{USS|Gamble|DD-123|2}}, {{USS|Breese|DD-122|2}}, and {{USS|Tracy|DD-214|2}} had laid mines at its western entrance. An investigation revealed that ''Tucker's'' captain had not been informed of the minefield.{{sfn|Rohwer|2005|p=184}} She was stricken from the ''[[Naval Vessel Register]]'' on 2{{nbsp}}December 1944.{{sfn|NHHC}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s loss was a setback to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]], which was trying to assemble every available ship for the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}}\n\nThree days after ''Tucker'' sank, the seagoing tugboat {{USS|Navajo|AT-64|2}} arrived on site with divers, [[marine salvage|salvaging]] her guns, turbines, anchors and chains. During the remainder of the war, the Navy used the wreckage site for diver training; they did not undertake further salvaging. \nSettling in just {{convert|60|ft}} of water, the ship was easily accessible to private salvors, who harvested anything of value, ransacking and further scattering ''Tucker''{{'}}s remains. Sport divers also had a destructive effect on the site, which by 1997 resembled an \"underwater junkyard\".{{sfn|Stone|1997|pp=78\u201379}} Mike Gerken, an underwater photojournalist, dove the ''Tucker'' wreckage site several times; in 2013 he eulogized ''Tucker'' and other sunken ships:\n\n{{quote\n|text=To see a ship with a distinguished record as the ''Tucker'' in such a poor state gave me pause for thought. I pondered that wrecks, like the ''Tucker'', will gradually disappear and to be saddened by this inevitable fact would be pointless. What is important is that the memory of these ships be kept alive by telling their stories.\n|author=Mike Gerken\n|title=\"The USS ''Tucker'': A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End\"\n|source=''Wreck Diving Magazine''{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n}}\n\n''Tucker'' and [[SS President Coolidge|SS ''President Coolidge'']], a troopship, suffered similar fates less than three months apart; both were sunk in different locations of the same U.S. Navy minefield, and both later became diving sites.{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n\n==Honors==\n''Tucker'' received one [[battle star]] for her [[World War II]] service.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=69}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|author=<nowiki>Conway's Maritime Editors</nowiki>|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|year=1980|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-913-8|ref={{SfnRef|Conway's|1980}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Norman|year=2004|title=U.S. Destroyers|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-55750-442-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://www.evolutionunderwater.com/uss-tucker|title=USS Tucker: A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End|last=Gerken|first=Mike|magazine=Wreck Diving Magazine|issue=31|date=2013|accessdate=27 October 2019|via=EvolutionUnderwater.com|ref={{sfnref|Gerken|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodges|first1=Peter|last2=Friedman|first2= Norman|year=1979|title=Destroyer Weapons of World War 2|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-929-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|author=NHHC|title=Tucker|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html|publisher=[[Naval History and Heritage Command]]|accessdate=26 April 2016|ref={{SfnRef|NHHC}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Parkin|first=Robert Sinclair|title=Blood on the Sea: American Destroyers Lost in World War II|url=https://archive.org/details/bloodonseaameric00park|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Sarpedon|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-885119-17-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reilly|first=John|date=1983|title=United States Navy Destroyers of World War II|location=Poole, Dorset, England|publisher=Blandford Press|isbn=0-7137-1026-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesnavy0000reil}}\n*{{cite book|last=Roscoe|first=Theodore|title=U.S. Destroyer  Operations in World War II|date=1953|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=0-87021-726-7|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesdest0000rosc}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945|date=2005|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=1-59114-119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Peter|title=The Lady and the President: The Life and Loss of the S. S. President Coolidge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THyca-AHdOEC&pg=PA79|year=1997|publisher=Oceans Enterprises|location=Yarram, Australia|isbn=978-0-95866572-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html}}\n\n===External links===\n*{{cite web |last1=Stone (2)|first1=Peter |title=The Lady and the President, The Life and Loss of the SS President Coolidge |url=http://www.oceans.com.au/pc.html |publisher=Oceans Enterprises |accessdate=24 November 2019}}\n{{Mahan class destroyer}}\n{{August 1942 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tucker (DD-374)}}\n[[Category:1936 ships]]\n[[Category:Attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n[[Category:Mahan-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1942]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Portsmouth, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Ships present during the attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by mines]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Massachusetts-related ships]]\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II shipwrecks in the Pacific Ocean]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|USS Tucker}}\n{{short description|Mahan-class destroyer}}\n{{coord missing|Pacific Ocean}}\n{{good article}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Tucker DD-374.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Tucker'' off the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]], [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], 2{{nbsp}}March 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1942}}\n|Ship name=''Tucker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Samuel Tucker]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Norfolk Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=15 August 1934\n|Ship launched=26 February 1936\n|Ship commissioned=23 July 1936\n|Ship struck=2 December 1944\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Struck [[Naval mine|mine]] off [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]], 4{{nbsp}}August 1942\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=(as built)\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|1500|LT|t|0|lk=in}} ([[standard load]])\n*{{convert|1725|LT|t}} ([[deep load]])\n|Ship length={{convert|341|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship power=*{{convert|46,000|shp|lk=on}}\n*4 [[water-tube boiler]]s           \n|Ship propulsion=2 [[Propeller shaft|shafts]] 2 geared [[steam turbine]]s\n|Ship speed={{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship complement=158 officers and enlisted men\n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[gun director]] above bridge\n|Ship armament=*5 \u00d7 single [[5\"/38 caliber gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}]] [[DP gun]]s\n*3 \u00d7 quadruple [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 in (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*4 \u00d7 single [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] AA machine guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] stern racks\n*Depth charge projectors (aka [[K-guns]])\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Tucker'' (DD-374)''' was a {{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]] and was commissioned in 1936. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]].\n\nFirst assigned to the [[United States Battle Fleet]] in [[San Diego]], [[California]], ''Tucker'' operated along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] and in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. After participating in [[naval exercise]]s in the [[Caribbean Sea]], she returned to duty in [[Territory of Hawaii|Hawaii]]. She then went on a goodwill tour to New Zealand, returning to Hawaii and docking at [[Pearl Harbor]]. When the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7{{nbsp}}December 1941, ''Tucker'' was undergoing an overhaul and was not attacked. Soon afterward, she began escorting convoys between the West Coast and Hawaii. ''Tucker'' was then tasked with escort duty to islands in the [[South Pacific Ocean|Sourth Pacific]].\n\n''Tucker'' steamed out of port on 1 August 1942, escorting a [[cargo ship]] to [[Espiritu Santo]]. They entered its harbor three days later, where the destroyer unknowingly entered a defensive [[minefield]] laid by the US Navy. ''Tucker'' struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]] that tore her almost in two, sinking her and killing three sailors; the rest of the crew survived.\n\n==Design==\n\n===General characteristics===  \nThe [[Mahan-class destroyer]]s were improved versions of the preceding [[Farragut-class destroyer (1934)|''Farragut'' class]].{{sfn|Reiilly| 1983| p=28}} The ''Mahan''s' [[standard displacement]] was {{convert|150|LT|t|0|lk=in}} larger, and they were equipped with a more efficient steam [[propulsion]] system and designed to carry 12 torpedo tubes, an increase of four over the Farragut-class.  \n{{snf|Friedman| 2004| p=88}} \n\n''Tucker'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|1500|LT|t|0|lk=on}}\nat [[standard load]] and {{convert|1725|LT|t}} at [[deep load]]. The ship's [[length overall|overall length]] was {{convert|341|ft|m|1}}, her [[beam (nautical)|beam]] was {{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|1}}, and her [[draft (hull)|draft]] was {{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|1}}. Her peace-time complement consisted of 158 officers and enlisted men.{{snf|Friedman|2004|pp=465\u2013466}}\n\nShe had a [[Tripod mast|tripod]] [[foremast]] and a pole mainmast. To improve the [[antiaircraft]] [[field of fire (weaponry)|field of fire]], her [[tripod]] foremast was constructed without nautical [[rigging]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}} The destroyer was fitted with emergency [[diesel generators]], replacing the storage batteries of earlier destroyers. Gun crew shelters were also built fore and aft for the superimposed guns. A third set of quadruple torpedo tubes was added, with one mounted on the [[centerline (nautical)|centerline]] and two in the side positions.{{sfn |Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n===Machinery and armament===\n''Tucker'' was fitted with four [[water-tube boiler]]s built by either [[Babcock & Wilcox]] or [[Foster Wheeler]]. They generated the steam that propelled the two [[General Electric]] geared [[steam turbine]]s, developing {{convert|46,000|shp|abbr=on|lk=on}} for a maximum speed of {{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}. ''Tucker'' carried a maximum of {{convert|523|LT|t}} of [[fuel oil]], with a trial range of {{convert|7300|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}. The ship's\nwartime ranges were {{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}} and {{convert|4360|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|20|kn|lk=in}}.\nThe ship's design incorporated a new generation of land-based propulsion machinery. The boilers were capable of reaching {{convert|650\u2013700|F|C|sigfig=2}}, powering the high-pressure turbines with [[double reduction gearing|double reduction gears]] that enabled the turbines to run faster and more efficiently than in previous destroyer designs.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]], equipped with the MK{{nbsp}}33 gun [[fire-control system]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} \nThe ship's antiaircraft battery had four water-cooled [[.50 caliber machine gun]]s (12.7&nbsp;mm).{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=111}} The ship was fitted with three quadruple torpedo-tube mounts for twelve {{convert|21|in|mm|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo]]es, guided by the Mark{{nbsp}}27 torpedo fire-control system. Each of the three mounts held four torpedoes. Those on the [[Port and starboard|port]] and [[Port and starboard|starboard]] sides could only fire [[broadside]], but the centerline mount could fire from either side.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} She was rigged for two [[depth charge]] roll-off racks and for depth charge projectors (K-guns).{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=86}} In early 1942, the Navy began to refit the ''Mahan''-class destroyers with new antiaircraft armament, although most of the class was not refitted until sometime in 1944. (The source, Hodges and Friedman, do not indicate if Tucker was refitted). {{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=145}}\n\n==Construction and service history==\n\n''Tucker'' was one of eighteen [[Mahan-class destroyer|Mahan-class destroyers]] and was built at the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]].{{sfn|Conway's|1980|pp=125\u2013126}} She was the second vessel to be named for [[Samuel Tucker]], who had been an officer in the [[Continental Navy]] and the United States Navy.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=67}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[keel]] was laid down on 15{{nbsp}}August 1934. She was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 26{{nbsp}}February 1936 and [[Ceremonial ship launching|christened]] by a third cousin of Tucker. The ship was commissioned in the United States Navy on 23{{nbsp}}July, with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] George T. Howard in command.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68-69}}\n\n[[File:USS Tucker.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval warship rigged with sails|''Tucker'' rigged with sails, June 1940]]\nAfter her [[shakedown cruise]], she joined destroyer forces attached to the United States Battle Fleet in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. She operated with them along the West Coast and in the Hawaiian islands as part of Destroyer Squadron{{nbsp}}3 of the Destroyer Division.\nIn February 1939, she took part in [[Fleet Problem&nbsp;XX]], a naval exercise held in the Caribbean Sea and Atlantic Ocean and observed by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. As tensions with Japan increased, the fleet was ordered to return to Hawaiian waters.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nIn June 1940, ''Tucker'' steamed from Hawaii to a location east of [[Wake Island]] for fleet exercises. In ''United States Navy Destroyers of World War II,'' John Reilly, Jr. described the uncommon method used to power the vessel on its return to Hawaii: {{blockquote|... Tucker stretched her fuel supply by rigging Sails. Her homemade [[foresail]] and [[mainsail]] moved Tucker at an estimated 3.4 knots, letting her maintain [[Glossary of nautical terms#steerageway|steerageway]] as she loitered on station several days.{{sfn|Reilly|1983|p=30}}}}\n\n''Tucker'' continued operating between Hawaii and the West Coast into February 1941. She then set course for New Zealand on a goodwill tour, arriving in [[Auckland]] on 17 March. Returning to Pearl Harbor, she took part in routine exercises at sea before returning to her homeport of San Diego on 19{{nbsp}}September. After a short stay, ''Tucker'' steamed to Hawaii in November as part of Task Force{{nbsp}}19, operating again in the Hawaiian Islands. Shortly afterward, she put into Pearl Harbor for an overhaul by a [[destroyer tender]].{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nWhen the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941, ''Tucker'' was one of five destroyers moored at berth X\u20139, East Loch, alongside the destroyer tender {{USS|Whitney|AD-4|2}}.{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|pp=47\u201348}} Even before ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[general quarters]] alarm could be sounded, one of her on-deck sailors began firing a 50-caliber machine gun at the first wave of Japanese aircraft. When the second wave attacked, every ship that could opened fire. ''Tucker''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on at least two aircraft: one crashed in a cane field, another in flames disappeared over a mountaintop. Because ''Tucker'' was at Pearl Harbor for overhaul, much of her machinery had been torn down for repairs; despite the crew's efforts, they were unable to get the ship underway until that evening.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68}}\n\nAfter her overhaul, ''Tucker'' patrolled off Pearl Harbor and spent several months escorting convoys between Hawaii and the West Coast. With new orders, she steamed to the South Pacific for convoy duty. ''Tucker'' then escorted the auxiliary ship {{USS|Wright|AV-1|2}} to [[Tutuila]], [[American Samoa]], as part of the drive to fortify outposts. She then escorted her charge to [[Suva]], [[British Fiji|Fiji]], and proceeded to [[Noumea]], [[New Caledonia]]. Steaming on for Australia, she arrived at [[Sydney]] on 27{{nbsp}}April. After taking on fuel, she visited [[Melbourne]], [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] before steaming back to Sydney. ''Tucker'' and  ''Wright'' returned to Suva, arriving on 3{{nbsp}}June 1942. For the remainder of June and into the first week of July, ''Tucker'' operated out of Suva before relieving the cruiser {{USS|Boise|CL-47|2}} of convoy escort duties on 10{{nbsp}}July. On{{nbsp}}30 July, the ship arrived at Auckland and the following day started back for Suva.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\n==Fate==\n[[Image:DD-374 sunk 5Aug1942 EspirituSanto NAN09-10-86.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval ship struck by a mine and sinking|USS ''Tucker'' (D-374) sinking south of Espiritu Santo,  5 August 1942]]\n\nOn 1{{nbsp}}August 1942 ''Tucker'' left Suva, escorting the cargo ship SS ''Nira Luckenbach'' to [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]].{{sfn|NHHC}} On 4{{nbsp}}August ''Tucker'' led the cargo ship into the harbor at Espiritu Santo, as she headed into the western entrance, she struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]]. The explosion tore her hull nearly in two at the [[Funnel (ship)|No.{{nbsp}}1 stack]], killing all three crew members on watch in the forward [[fire room]]. The rest of the ship's company survived.\n''Nira Luckenbach'' and other vessels rescued sailors from their sinking ship. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[stern]] sank the following morning; a diving party scuttled and sank her [[bow (ship)|bow]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}} The ship had steamed into the [[Segond Channel]] unaware that the minelayers {{USS|Gamble|DD-123|2}}, {{USS|Breese|DD-122|2}}, and {{USS|Tracy|DD-214|2}} had laid mines at its western entrance. An investigation revealed that ''Tucker's'' captain had not been informed of the minefield.{{sfn|Rohwer|2005|p=184}} She was stricken from the ''[[Naval Vessel Register]]'' on 2{{nbsp}}December 1944.{{sfn|NHHC}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s loss was a setback to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]], which was trying to assemble every available ship for the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}}\n\nThree days after ''Tucker'' sank, the seagoing tugboat {{USS|Navajo|AT-64|2}} arrived on site with divers, [[marine salvage|salvaging]] her guns, turbines, anchors and chains. During the remainder of the war, the Navy used the wreckage site for diver training; they did not undertake further salvaging. \nSettling in just {{convert|60|ft}} of water, the ship was easily accessible to private salvors, who harvested anything of value, ransacking and further scattering ''Tucker''{{'}}s remains. Sport divers also had a destructive effect on the site, which by 1997 resembled an \"underwater junkyard\".{{sfn|Stone|1997|pp=78\u201379}} Mike Gerken, an underwater photojournalist, dove the ''Tucker'' wreckage site several times; in 2013 he eulogized ''Tucker'' and other sunken ships:\n\n{{quote\n|text=To see a ship with a distinguished record as the ''Tucker'' in such a poor state gave me pause for thought. I pondered that wrecks, like the ''Tucker'', will gradually disappear and to be saddened by this inevitable fact would be pointless. What is important is that the memory of these ships be kept alive by telling their stories.\n|author=Mike Gerken\n|title=\"The USS ''Tucker'': A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End\"\n|source=''Wreck Diving Magazine''{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n}}\n\n''Tucker'' and [[SS President Coolidge|SS ''President Coolidge'']], a troopship, suffered similar fates less than three months apart; both were sunk in different locations of the same U.S. Navy minefield, and both later became diving sites.{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n\n==Honors==\n''Tucker'' received one [[battle star]] for her [[World War II]] service.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=69}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|author=<nowiki>Conway's Maritime Editors</nowiki>|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|year=1980|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-913-8|ref={{SfnRef|Conway's|1980}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Norman|year=2004|title=U.S. Destroyers|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-55750-442-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://www.evolutionunderwater.com/uss-tucker|title=USS Tucker: A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End|last=Gerken|first=Mike|magazine=Wreck Diving Magazine|issue=31|date=2013|accessdate=27 October 2019|via=EvolutionUnderwater.com|ref={{sfnref|Gerken|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodges|first1=Peter|last2=Friedman|first2= Norman|year=1979|title=Destroyer Weapons of World War 2|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-929-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|author=NHHC|title=Tucker|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html|publisher=[[Naval History and Heritage Command]]|accessdate=26 April 2016|ref={{SfnRef|NHHC}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Parkin|first=Robert Sinclair|title=Blood on the Sea: American Destroyers Lost in World War II|url=https://archive.org/details/bloodonseaameric00park|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Sarpedon|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-885119-17-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reilly|first=John|date=1983|title=United States Navy Destroyers of World War II|location=Poole, Dorset, England|publisher=Blandford Press|isbn=0-7137-1026-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesnavy0000reil}}\n*{{cite book|last=Roscoe|first=Theodore|title=U.S. Destroyer  Operations in World War II|date=1953|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=0-87021-726-7|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesdest0000rosc}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945|date=2005|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=1-59114-119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Peter|title=The Lady and the President: The Life and Loss of the S. S. President Coolidge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THyca-AHdOEC&pg=PA79|year=1997|publisher=Oceans Enterprises|location=Yarram, Australia|isbn=978-0-95866572-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html}}\n\n===External links===\n*{{cite web |last1=Stone (2)|first1=Peter |title=The Lady and the President, The Life and Loss of the SS President Coolidge |url=http://www.oceans.com.au/pc.html |publisher=Oceans Enterprises |accessdate=24 November 2019}}\n{{Mahan class destroyer}}\n{{August 1942 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tucker (DD-374)}}\n[[Category:1936 ships]]\n[[Category:Attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n[[Category:Mahan-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1942]]\n[[Category:Ships built in 